# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: archaeology
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] The **1966 flood of the Arno** (Italian: *Alluvione di Firenze del 4 novembre 1966*) in Florence killed 35 people and damaged or destroyed millions of masterpieces of art and rare books.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] It is considered the worst flood in the city's history since 1557.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] With the combined effort of Italian and foreign volunteers alike, or *angeli del fango* ("Mud Angels"), many of these fine works have been restored.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] New methods in conservation were devised and restoration laboratories established.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] However, even decades later, much work remains to be done.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] Located in the Tuscany region of Central Italy, the river Arno is approximately 240 kilometres (150 mi) long.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] It flows from the Mount Falterona hills of the Apennine Mountains to the Ligurian Sea, just 11 kilometres (7 mi) west of Pisa.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] Lush vineyards and olive groves line the river's scenic course to the west, out to sea.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] Principally utilized for irrigation purposes, only 32 kilometres (20 mi) of the river is used for navigation.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] The highest flows of the river generally occur in spring and autumn of every year, when rainfall in the Apennines is at its greatest.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] The intensity of the 1966 flood was further increased by both the topography of the Apennines, which contributed to the high run-off rates and river discharges, and urban development.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] Roads, such as the Via dei Calzaiuoli, served as narrow channels for floodwaters, allowing for their greater speed and destruction within the city; bridges, on the other hand, hindered river flow where it was needed, allowing water to pour over the floodplain with great force.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] The flood has had a lasting impact on Florence, economically and culturally.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] City officials and citizens were unprepared for the storm and the widespread devastation that it caused.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] There were virtually no emergency measures in place, at least partially because Florence is located in an area where the frequency of flooding is relatively low.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] In fact, approximately 90% of the city's population were completely unaware of the imminent disaster.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] Residents were set to celebrate their country's World War I victory over Austria on 4 November, Armed Forces Day.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] In commemoration, businesses were closed and many of their employees were out of town for the public holiday.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] While many lives were likely spared as a result, the locked buildings greatly inhibited the salvaging of valuable materials from numerous institutions and shops, with the exception of a number of jewellery stores whose owners were warned by their nightwatchmen.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] 6,000 shops were destroyed, more than 70,000 families were left homeless, 20,000 cars were immersed in the water and mud, and thousands of workshops, factories, laboratories and stores were flooded.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] Approximately 600,000 tons of mud, rubble and sewage severely damaged or destroyed numerous collections of books, manuscripts and fine art.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] It is estimated that between 3 and 4 million books and manuscripts were damaged, as well as 14,000 movable works of art.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] Artist Marco Sassone, in a 1969 interview, recalled the impact of the flood on Florence's residents: "The only thing you could do was watch and be helpless.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] Nature was master...the women became crazy with fear.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] They began throwing things from the windows and screaming 'who is going to save my children?'" It was reported that 101 people lost their lives in the flood waters.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] Realizing the immense wealth and importance of Florentine culture in a global context, many individuals and organizations contributed to the conservation mission, providing both funding and manpower.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] Art historian and professor Carlo Ludovico Ragghianti assembled an Italian committee (Comitato Fondo Internazionale per Firenze) with Mayor Piero Bargellini as chairman to raise awareness of the needs of Florence's art and academic institutions.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] Members included prominent figures from around the world, representatives of their own respective institutions.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] The recovery of Florence's cultural heritage involved an extensive international network of scholars, conservators, and organisations.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] The work of and contributions made by these committees were supervised by a central committee in Rome.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] The flood prompted the creation of national committees in multiple countries to support heritage rescue and recovery in Florence.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] Scholars have described differences between national responses in terms of organisational form, public engagement, and the relative emphasis placed on fundraising, coordination, and longer-term support.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] Sources on the heritage response emphasise that media circulation and public-facing fundraising were important tools for mobilising international support beyond the immediate emergency phase.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] Kumar (2023) identifies recurring frames used in CRIA communications and U.S. press coverage—emphasising damage, rescue and restoration, the committee's actions, and the cultural value of Florence—to encourage donations and participation.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] Retrospective accounts also describe how Franco Zeffirelli's film *Florence: Days of Destruction* circulated through fundraising networks and associated screenings, helping sustain attention and support for recovery efforts.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] Its activities included public appeals, the shipment of conservation materials, and support for expert involvement in Florence.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] Art historian Sydney Joseph Freedberg is recorded as serving as national vice chairman of CRIA (1966–74).
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] Contemporary reporting also describes art historian Bates Lowry as heading the U.S. committee and organising fundraising in response to the Florence flood.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] In the conservation field, book and paper conservator Carolyn Price Horton is described as being involved in Florence flood recovery work and connected with CRIA-related efforts.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] The flood is frequently discussed as a major catalyst for modern preservation and conservation practice, particularly in libraries and archives.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] Additional funding came from various governments, UNESCO, and the International Committee for the Assistance of Museums, Works of Art, Libraries and Archives, among others.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] The city of Edinburgh (Scotland), twinned with Florence, sent practical help for the citizens in the form of double-decker buses to temporarily replace those which had been lost in the floods.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] When these eventually returned home, they operated with the international 'GB' registration plate still affixed to the rear; each also carried a small plaque presented by the Florentine transport authorities indicating their gratitude for the gesture made by the people of Edinburgh.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] In a show of support for the Florentine art community, Pablo Picasso had one of his paintings, *Recumbent Woman Reading*, auctioned off on an internationally televised programme.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] He donated the $105,000 it earned to restoration efforts in Italy.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] Similarly, Pietro Annigoni and Luciano Guarnieri donated the money they earned from selling 575 colour lithographs (depicting the events surrounding the flood and its aftermath), produced from 13 of their drawings.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] Florentine native Franco Zeffirelli produced the short documentary *Florence: Days of Destruction* to raise awareness of the flood.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] Released a month after the disaster, it reputedly raised more than $20 million for reconstruction efforts.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] The film was narrated in English and Italian by actor Richard Burton.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] People from Aberfan, Wales sent parcels with toys and clothes to Florence, which had belonged to the children who had died during the Aberfan disaster two weeks earlier.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] While many institutions from around the world financially compensated employees who travelled to Italy and aided in the restoration of Florence, many others volunteered their services for absolutely no pay.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] Collectively, these people have been fondly referred to as "Mud Angels".
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] While the article lists several initiatives, sources indicate that national responses differed in scale, public engagement strategies, and the balance between fundraising, coordination, and field-based activity.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] Scholarship describes the United States' response as highly visible and media-driven through the celebrity-backed Committee to Rescue Italian Art (CRIA), while the United Kingdom also organised fundraising and institutional support through the Italian Art and Archives Rescue Fund (IAARF).
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] The Italian Art and Archvies Rescue Fund (IAARF) also focused on the floods in Venice.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] The charity Venice in Peril Fund succeeded IAARF and still works in protecting heritage of Venice.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] Although Wikipedia notes the arrival of aid and references Franco Zeffirelli's film *Florence: Days of Destruction*, sources suggest that media circulation and public-facing fundraising were central tools for mobilising international support.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] Kumar (2023) identifies recurring frames used by CRIA and U.S. press coverage—emphasising damage, rescue and restoration, the committee's actions, and the cultural value of Florence—to encourage donations and participation.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] Retrospective accounts also describe how Zeffirelli's film circulated through fundraising networks and screenings associated with relief campaigns, helping sustain attention beyond the immediate disaster period.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] Mario Primicerio, the mayor of Florence from 1995 to 1999, helped celebrate the Mud Angels' (*angeli del fango*) efforts during an anniversary celebration in 1996.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] Thirty years earlier, he was a professor who lent his assistance in preserving the priceless artifacts of Florence.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] The Angels cleaned the city of refuse, mud and oil, and retrieved works of art, books and other materials from flooded rooms; experts from around the world volunteered their time and knowledge in the conservation of the aforementioned materials.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] In a 1996 interview, Primicerio offered three principal reasons as to why the Mud Angels felt compelled to help: a concern for future generations, a feeling of international unity and a pervasive sense of solidarity.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] The Flood Ladies were a group of international female artists who contributed artworks to the city of Florence following the catastrophic 1966 flood of the Arno as a sign of solidarity and to help repair the psychological damage done by the flood.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] The group was formed in Florence, Italy in 1966.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] Contributors to the collection lived all over the world.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] In 2014 the organization Advancing Women Artists Foundation headed an effort to preserve, exhibit and acknowledge the contribution of these women.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] Many experts in the field of conservation, such as Peter Waters, utilised their knowledge in restoring the works of art and literature ravaged by the flood.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] Staff from the Central Institute of Restoration and Institute of Book Pathology, for example, volunteered their time, efforts, and expertise in this enormous undertaking.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] New concepts, such as "phased conservation", and methods in conservation, such as mass deacidification, were conceived during this period after the flood ravaged the city of Florence.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] Priorities were established during the process of conserving damaged books and records, the most critical of which became the retrieval of materials from flooded rooms.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] After they were rescued, books and records were typically washed and disinfected.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] In certain cases, bindings were cut and sheets treated individually.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] Following a thorough cleansing, the materials were then dried in Florentine libraries, space permitting, or at locations outside of the city, such as tobacco kilns and granaries.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] In some circumstances, large numbers of books were covered with sawdust, as a means of drawing out moisture.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] When not washed prior to drying, dried mud was then scraped off the exterior of the books.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] One or both of two drying techniques was applied: interleaving by hand and/or drying with the aid of domestic heaters or other mechanical equipment.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] Interleaving involved the placement of blotting papers within the text-block of a book and replacing them once they were fully soaked; a variety of papers were used, including mimeograph paper and green blotting paper (the latter of which ultimately caused more damage).
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] In kilns, the humidity level was slowly lowered from ninety to forty percent.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] If deemed necessary, bindings were removed and dried separately.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] Removed pages were hung out to dry on an apparatus similar to a clothes line.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] Fearing the spread of mold, workers completed these tasks with the greatest speed possible.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] After they were disinfected and dried, the items were then reassembled, restored and, if necessary, rebound.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] Card catalogs and in some cases, the actual books and documents were reproduced by reprinting on early presses, photocopying, or copying by hand.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] Initially the transportation of large numbers of books to other institutes (to repair and rebind) was considered, but decided against on logistical grounds.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] British book conservator Anthony Cains was appointed Technical Director of Conservation for the library in 1967 and remained for six years, supervising recovery efforts.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] Within six months of the flood, the National Library of Florence had 144 workers on hand: three binders, eight binder trainees, two librarians, forty-two workmen, eighty-one student volunteers and eight other library staff members.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] This methodical nine-part system enabled workers to process between seventy and a hundred books a day.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] After the Florence flood, the Biblioteca Nazionale Centrale was not allowed to put books back into the lower levels.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] The disaster also accelerated the adoption of techniques such as heat-set tissue repair, polyester encapsulation, and mass deacidification, which later became standard practices in research libraries.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] Many panel paintings were critically damaged as a result of water saturating their wood, causing the glue and gesso, which compose the priming layer, to dissolve.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] Consequently, the paintings' colours dissolved as well.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] In addition, the moisture caused paintings to buckle and crack or develop blisters, and the paint to chip and fall.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] Actions were taken to stabilize the problem by applying mulberry paper to the affected paintings and storing them in cool, stable environments where humidity was slowly decreased.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] In extreme cases, the paint layer was extracted from the wood and gesso and then reapplied to a new support.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] Nystatin, an antifungal, was sprayed on the wood to prevent mold from growing.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] Treatment facilities were established at locations such as the Boboli Garden Lemon-House, where over two hundred of these panel paintings were restored.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] Similar measures were necessary to conserve canvas paintings.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] First, an original canvas was relined and gauze applied to the painted surface, which was then ironed.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] This process is referred to as the *rintelatura*, or "new canvas" method.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] Relatively minor surface work was often completed with a variety of solvents and/or types of resin.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] Frescoes demanded more complicated treatment.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] Normally water, once it evaporates, will leave a layer of residual salt on the surface of the wall that absorbed it.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] In some instances, the resultant efflorescence obscured painted images.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] In other cases, the impermeability of the fresco plaster caused the salt to become trapped beneath the surface, causing bubbles to form and erupt, and the paint to fall.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] The adhesion of the plaster to the wall was often also seriously compromised.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] A fresco could only be detached when fully dry.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] To dry a fresco, workers cut narrow tunnels beneath it, in which heaters were placed to draw out moisture from below (instead of outwards, which would have further damaged the paintings).
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] Within a few days, the fresco was ready to be detached.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] Fuel oil, which coated many painted works of art, was removed by using Japanese tissue paper to apply a solvent, which dissolved the tar.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] An absorbent, such as talcum powder, was then distributed on the tissue paper.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] It became imperative to clean sculpture immediately, before it fully absorbed the oil.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] Flaking sculpture was sprayed with a silicate mixture, while wooden pieces were treated with insecticides and toxic gases to kill insects and prevent future infestation.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] Weaponry, like firearms and swords, were taken apart, cleaned with paraffin, and finally lubricated to prevent future rusting.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] Bronze objects were kept in dehumidification chambers for a few weeks and cleaned with distilled water or polished.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] For more severely damaged pieces, experts completed "depth cleaning", which entailed the use of small drills and vacuuming.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] Broken objects were reassembled using photographs and other retrieved documentation.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] The disastrous results of the flood established an international awareness of the need for preservation and conservation education and facilities.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] It is no coincidence that the National Historic Preservation Act was passed in the United States in 1966.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] Carolyn Price Horton was one of the "Mud Angels" sent to Florence by the Committee to Rescue Italian Art (CRIA).
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] The American Library Association published Horton's *Cleaning and Preserving Bindings and Related Materials* in 1967, and republished it in 1969.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] The floods of November 1966 affected both Florence and Venice, but the nature of damage and conservation responses differed.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] In Florence, the Arno River caused extensive damage to movable cultural heritage, including books, manuscripts, and artworks.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] Recovery efforts focused on emergency salvage and the development of large-scale conservation techniques, particularly in libraries such as the Biblioteca Nazionale Centrale di Firenze.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] In Venice, flooding associated with *acqua alta* primarily affected buildings and urban infrastructure.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] Conservation efforts have therefore focused more on long-term environmental management, including responses to saltwater damage and ongoing flood risk.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] Scholars note that Florence relied heavily on international volunteers and public fundraising, including initiatives such as the Committee to Rescue Italian Art (CRIA), while Venice's response has been more closely tied to sustained governmental and infrastructural strategies.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] Comparative studies suggest that Florence represents a model of post-disaster recovery, whereas Venice illustrates long-term heritage risk management.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] A significant amount of restorative work remains to be done in Florence.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] Due to a lack of awareness, funding, and manpower, a great number of works of art and books lie in storage, dirty and damaged.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] Christopher Clarkson, noted conservator, called attention to this problem in a 2007 letter, stating that the National Library still has a "warehouse" full of books to be repaired and bound; many others need cleaning or reassembling.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] According to a 1993 report, approximately 25% of the 80,000 items belonging to the Magliabecchi and Palatino collections had not been fully restored in the nearly thirty years since the flood.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] The number of conservators that work at the library presently is only about a tenth of the amount that worked there immediately after the flood.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] The 1966 Florence flood had a lasting impact on the development of modern preservation practices in libraries, archives, and museums.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] It encouraged a shift from individual object restoration toward collection-wide management, prioritisation, and preventive conservation.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] The large-scale recovery effort contributed to the adoption of systematic workflows and approaches such as phased conservation, later applied in major institutions including the Library of Congress.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] The flood also highlighted the importance of disaster preparedness and international cooperation, and is widely regarded as a formative event in the development of modern conservation policy and practice.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] Regional officials in Tuscany are responsible for organizing a massive project, the purpose of which is to not only protect the area from future flooding but to maintain high water quality and effectively utilize water resources.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] Work commenced in 1984, with the construction of the Bilancino Dam, near Florence.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] The Sieve tributary and spillway at Pontedera are among other developments.
[src:archaeology/1966-flood-of-the-arno] The national government has funded a majority of these various subprojects, with the city of Florence being the primary recipient of the money.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] In 3D computer graphics, **3D modeling** is the process of developing a mathematical coordinate-based representation of a surface of an object (inanimate or living) in three dimensions via specialized software by manipulating edges, vertices, and polygons in a simulated 3D space.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] Three-dimensional (3D) models represent a physical body using a collection of points in 3D space, connected by various geometric entities such as triangles, lines, curved surfaces, etc.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] Being a collection of data (points and other information), 3D models can be created manually, algorithmically (procedural modeling), or by scanning.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] Their surfaces may be further defined with texture mapping.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] The product is called a 3D model, while someone who works with 3D models may be referred to as a 3D artist or a 3D modeler.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] A 3D model can also be displayed as a two-dimensional image through a process called 3D rendering or used in a computer simulation of physical phenomena.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] 3D models may be created automatically or manually.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] The manual modeling process of preparing geometric data for 3D computer graphics is similar to plastic arts such as sculpting.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] The 3D model can be physically created using 3D printing devices that form 2D layers of the model with three-dimensional material, one layer at a time.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] Without a 3D model, a 3D print is not possible.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] 3D modeling software is a class of 3D computer graphics software used to produce 3D models.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] Individual programs of this class are called modeling applications.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] 3D models are now widely used anywhere in 3D graphics and CAD but their history predates the widespread use of 3D graphics on personal computers.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] In the past, many computer games used pre-rendered images of 3D models as sprites before computers could render them in real-time.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] The designer can then see the model in various directions and views, this can help the designer see if the object is created as intended to compared to their original vision.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] Seeing the design this way can help the designer or company figure out changes or improvements needed to the product.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] Simple wireframes were the first versions of early 3D models, which were mainly used to view construction plans and mechanical parts.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] Better graphics hardware and software allowed for the creation of solid and surface models in the 1970s and 1980s, giving designers a more realistic and clear representation of physical objects.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] By the 1990s, parametric modeling became popular, letting designers change a model by changing its basic parameters instead of redrawing it from scratch.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] Thanks to virtual reality, artificial intelligence and generative design tools, 3D modeling today goes past engineering and is influencing fields like animation, gaming, product design and cinema.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] Solid and shell modeling can create functionally identical objects.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] Differences between them are mostly variations in the way they are created and edited and conventions of use in various fields and differences in types of approximations between the model and reality.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] Shell models must be manifold (having no holes or cracks in the shell) to be meaningful as a real object.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] For example, in a shell model of a cube, all six sides must be connected with no gaps in the edges or the corners.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] Polygonal meshes (and to a lesser extent, subdivision surfaces) are by far the most common representation.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] Level sets are a useful representation for deforming surfaces that undergo many topological changes, such as fluids.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] The process of transforming representations of objects, such as the middle point coordinate of a sphere and a point on its circumference, into a polygon representation of a sphere is called tessellation.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] This step is used in polygon-based rendering, where objects are broken down from abstract representations ("primitives") such as spheres, cones etc., to so-called *meshes*, which are nets of interconnected triangles.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] Meshes of triangles (instead of e.g., squares) are popular as they have proven to be easy to rasterize (the surface described by each triangle is planar, so the projection is always convex).
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] Polygon representations are not used in all rendering techniques, and in these cases the tessellation step is not included in the transition from abstract representation to rendered scene.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] The modeling stage consists of shaping individual objects that are later used in the scene.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] In some cases, there is no strict distinction between these phases; in such cases, modeling is just part of the scene creation process (this is the case, for example, with Caligari trueSpace and Realsoft 3D).
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] 3D models can also be created using the technique of Photogrammetry with dedicated programs such as RealityCapture, Metashape and 3DF Zephyr.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] Cleanup and further processing can be performed with applications such as MeshLab, the GigaMesh Software Framework, netfabb or MeshMixer.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] Photogrammetry creates models using algorithms to interpret the shape and texture of real-world objects and environments based on photographs taken from many angles of the subject.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] Complex materials such as blowing sand, clouds, and liquid sprays are modeled with particle systems, and are a mass of 3D coordinates which have either points, polygons, texture splats or sprites assigned to them.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] There are a variety of 3D modeling programs that can be used in the industries of engineering, interior design, film and others.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] Each 3D modeling software has specific capabilities and can be utilized to fulfill demands for the industry.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] Many programs include export options to form a g-code, applicable to additive or subtractive manufacturing machinery.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] G-code (computer numerical control) works with automated technology to form a real-world rendition of 3D models.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] This code is a specific set of instructions to carry out steps of a product's manufacturing.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] The first widely available commercial application of human virtual models appeared in 1998 on the Lands' End web site.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] The human virtual models were created by the company My Virtual Mode Inc. and enabled users to create a model of themselves and try on 3D clothing.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] There are several modern programs that allow for the creation of virtual human models (Poser being one example).
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] The development of cloth simulation software such as Marvelous Designer, CLO3D and Optitex, has enabled artists and fashion designers to model dynamic 3D clothing on the computer.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] Dynamic 3D clothing is used for virtual fashion catalogs, as well as for dressing 3D characters for video games, 3D animation movies, for digital doubles in movies, as a creation tool for digital fashion brands, as well as for making clothes for avatars in virtual worlds such as SecondLife.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] 3D photorealistic effects are often achieved without wire-frame modeling and are sometimes indistinguishable in the final form.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] Some graphic art software includes filters that can be applied to 2D vector graphics or 2D raster graphics on transparent layers.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] Disadvantages compared to 2D photorealistic rendering may include a software learning curve and difficulty achieving certain photorealistic effects.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] Some photorealistic effects may be achieved with special rendering filters included in the 3D modeling software.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] For the best of both worlds, some artists use a combination of 3D modeling followed by editing the 2D computer-rendered images from the 3D model.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] A large market for 3D models (as well as 3D-related content, such as textures, scripts, etc.) exists—either for individual models or large collections.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] Several online marketplaces for 3D content allow individual artists to sell content that they have created, including TurboSquid, MyMiniFactory,Patreon,Sketchfab, CGTrader, and Cults.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] Often, the artists' goal is to get additional value out of assets they have previously created for projects.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] By doing so, artists can earn more money out of their old content, and companies can save money by buying pre-made models instead of paying an employee to create one from scratch.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] These marketplaces typically split the sale between themselves and the artist that created the asset, artists get 40% to 95% of the sales according to the marketplace.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] In most cases, the artist retains ownership of the 3D model while the customer only buys the right to use and present the model.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] Some artists sell their products directly in their own stores, offering their products at a lower price by not using intermediaries.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] The architecture, engineering and construction (AEC) industry is the biggest market for 3D modeling, with an estimated value of $12.13 billion by 2028.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] This is due to the increasing adoption of 3D modeling in the AEC industry, which helps to improve design accuracy, reduce errors and omissions and facilitate collaboration among project stakeholders.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] Over the last several years numerous marketplaces specializing in 3D rendering and printing models have emerged.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] Some of the 3D printing marketplaces are a combination of models sharing sites, with or without a built in e-com capability.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] Some of those platforms also offer 3D printing services on demand, software for model rendering and dynamic viewing of items.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] The term 3D printing or three-dimensional printing is a form of additive manufacturing technology where a three-dimensional object is created from successive layers of material.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] Objects can be created without the need for complex and expensive molds or assembly of multiple parts.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] 3D printing allows ideas to be prototyped and tested without having to go through a more time-consuming production process.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] 3D models can be purchased from online markets and printed by individuals or companies using commercially available 3D printers, enabling the home-production of objects such as spare parts and even medical equipment.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] Open-source tools (for instance Blender, FreeCAD, MeshLab, OpenSCAD) coexist with commercial packages (some examples are: Autodesk Maya/3ds Max/Fusion 360, SolidWorks, CATIA, Cinema 4D, ZBrush, Rhino, Houdini, SketchUp, CLO 3D/Marvelous Designer, Revit, Archicad).
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] The RDF representation of 3D models can be used in reasoning, which enables intelligent 3D applications which, for example, can automatically compare two 3D models by volume.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] Overall, these examples are an illustration of 3D modelling being a tool of general purpose representational layer that creates a bridge between sensing to analysis, design, communication and fabrication.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] Despite 3D modelling being widely adopted in various domains, several constraints shape how the technology is utilized.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] Access and cost remain an issue in many regions of the world.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] Commercial licences, training, and capable hardware can be difficult to find in select regions.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] It can also be out of reach for students and small studios that cannot afford it.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] Open-source ecosystems and school programs can aid in making this less of an issue, but availability and support are uneven which in turn creates an equity gap in who can learn and apply 3D modelling.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] Workflow complexity is another limitation.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] To practice 3D modelling effectively it requires knowledge of many different things.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] A 3D modelling specialist needs to understand topology, UV mapping, rigging, simulation and rendering for DCC.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] For CAD/CAM modelling parametric constraints, tolerances and manufacturing constraints must be known by the developer.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] Information schema and coordination are both required for BIM.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] Moving assets between tools can introduce incompatibility issues (meshes vs.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] NURBS/solids/parametric features; unit scaling; normals; material definitions), and format conversions may cause data loss without careful management.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] At scale, energy consumption can be large (this is due to high resolution simulations and rendering and dense 3D scans), which directs teams to try and optimize design complexity and adopting more efficient pipelines.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] In research and heritage work, there is another constraint where ethical and policy questions include provenance, licensing and representation (how “authoritative” a reconstruction should be labelled), especially as these reconstruction are utilized for public communication and educational purposes.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] Finally, classroom and outreach deployments must take into account pedagogical support: learners need step by step guidance and clear examples and models to follow.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] Without this, the tool’s complexity will be more of a barrier that slows students down instead of enabling them to understand and be creative.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] In 3D modeling, simulations are digital processes that copy how things behave in the real world, in a virtual space.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] Without creating actual prototypes, it lets designers and animators test how objects move, interact, or react to forces.
[src:archaeology/3d-modeling] By recreating processes such as collisions, fluid movement, fabric draping, or particle motion, simulations help increase design accuracy, enhance visual effects, and save both time and materials.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The **A14** is a major trunk road in England, running 127 miles (204 km) from the Catthorpe Interchange, a major intersection at the southern end of the M6 and junction 19 of the M1 in Leicestershire, to the port of Felixstowe, Suffolk.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The road forms part of the unsigned Euroroutes E24 and E30.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] It is the busiest shipping lane in East Anglia carrying anything from cars to large amounts of cargo between the UK and Mainland Europe.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] Beginning at the Catthorpe Interchange, the A14 runs through Kettering, Northamptonshire, towards Huntingdon where it now runs parallel to the A1 past Brampton, Cambridgeshire and now bypasses Huntingdon completely due to the A14 Cambridge to Huntingdon Scheme from 2017 until 2022.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] It continues past Bar Hill towards Cambridge to meet the end of the M11 and the A428 at the Girton Interchange.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The A14 continues easterly over northern Cambridge towards Newmarket where it briefly joins with the A11 to form the Newmarket Bypass between J36 and J38.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The A11 splits off again towards the North and the A14 continues through Bury St Edmunds, past Stowmarket then on to bypass Ipswich via the Orwell Bridge and finally comes to an end at the Port of Felixstowe fully connecting the Midlands to East Anglia.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] There is also a short dual four-lane section of the A14 that runs between Bar Hill and the Girton Interchange.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] There are three at-grade junctions: with the B663 at Bythorn in Cambridgeshire (junction 15); at the Leighton Bromswold turn a few miles to the east (junction 17); and at the Dockspur Roundabout at the edge of Felixstowe (junction 60).
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] There were two additional at-grade roundabouts along the former A14 main route, these being Brampton Hut Interchange (Junction 21) and Spittals Interchange (former Junction 23).
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] However, these junctions are no longer part of the A14 since the opening of the new alignment south of Huntingdon in December 2019.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The old A14 from Huntingdon Spittals interchange to Godmanchester was closed both ways for a 2-year period, and has now reopened in 2022 as part of the A1307, after the Huntingdon railway viaduct has been dismantled.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] Link roads at Hinchingbrooke and Mill Common will connect the former A14 dual carriageway to the road network in Huntingdon.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The original A14 was known as the Royston - Alconbury Trunk Road, the original A604 was known as the Barton Seagrave - Harwich Trunk Road, and the original A45 was known as the Ipswich - Weedon Trunk Road.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] Prior to the current A14, the main route from Birmingham to the Haven ports followed the M6, M1, A428 and A45 via Coventry, Rugby, Northampton, Bedford, St Neots and Cambridge, and then went through all the towns on the A14 to Felixstowe.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] Prior to its use for the current route, the A14 designation had been used for a section of road between the A10 at Royston and the A1 at Alconbury, following part of the route of Ermine Street which is now designated the A1198 to Godmanchester and the A1307 to Alconbury.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The section through Huntingdon is now part of the A1307 following the opening of the Huntingdon by-pass; Highways England demolished a viaduct carrying the road over the River Great Ouse and the Great Northern railway and built new junctions with local roads.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The M45 motorway was constructed in 1959 parallel to part of the old A45 in the Midlands.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] It opened on the same day as the M1 motorway and was soon one of the busiest sections of the motorway.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The M6 opened in the late 1960s and early 1970s, after which more traffic to the ports used the route from junction 1 of the M6 via the A427 to Market Harborough, followed by a short section of the A6 to Kettering and then the A604 to Cambridge, before joining the old A45 to the ports as above.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The sections from Huntingdon east to the ports were upgraded first, starting with the Huntingdon bypass in 1973, followed by the Girton to Bar Hill section in 1975/76 and the Cambridge northern bypass and Cambridge/Newmarket section in 1976/77.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The Bar Hill-to-Huntingdon section opened in 1979, prior to the M11 which was fully opened in 1980.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The Ipswich southern bypass, including the Orwell Bridge, opened between 1982 and 1985.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The A604 between Kettering and Huntingdon was upgraded and the section from Catthorpe to Kettering was constructed between 1989 and 1991 (commonly referred to at the time as the "M1-A1 link road") following a lengthy period of consultation.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The first inquiry was in 1974 and then a series of inquiries for sections of the preferred route from September 1984 until June 1985, during which objections came from some 1,130 sources.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] Subsequent public inquiries were held regarding Supplementary Orders.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The route close to the site of the Battle of Naseby was particularly difficult, and was taken to the High Court.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The link was opened by Transport Secretary John MacGregor on 15 July 1994.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] Work to create a compact grade-separated junction (Junction 45/Rougham) and to re-align a 2-mile (3.2 km) stretch of carriageway was completed in 2006.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The bans are active between 6am and 8pm, and are intended to reduce delays to other traffic from lorries attempting to pass on these climbs.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] Between 2007 and 2008 a new section of a two-lane dual carriageway was constructed at the Haughley Bends, one of Suffolk's most notorious accident blackspots, to rationalise access using a new grade-separated junction.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The road opened in the summer of 2008 with some associated local works being completed early in 2009.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] Variable Message Signs (VMS), traffic queue detection loops and closed circuit TV (CCTV) were installed at a cost of £50 million during 2009 to 2010 Both carriageways between Junction 52 (Claydon) and Junction 55 (Copdock) were refurbished during 2010 at a cost of £9 million.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] Work was being carried out a year earlier than scheduled as part of a UK government's fiscal stimulus package.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The Felixstowe and Nuneaton freight capacity scheme, designed to take more lorry traffic off the A14 between the Port and the Midlands by increasing rail capacity and allowing the carriage of larger 'Hi-cube' shipping containers by widening to the W10 loading gauge, opened in 2011.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] Junction 55 (Copdock interchange) to the south of Ipswich was equipped with signalisation in 2011, along with lengthening the off-slip from the A1214.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The section around Kettering between Junctions 7 and 9 was widened to three lanes between November 2013 and April 2015 at a cost of £42 million.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] After initially being shelved in 2010, the Catthorpe Interchange at the road's Western terminus underwent a massive restructuring in 2014.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The redesigned junction was intended to allow free-flowing traffic movement between the A14, the southern terminus of the M6 motorway and Junction 19 of the M1 motorway.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The first part opened in September 2016, and the upgrade was completed three months later.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The contract for the 6.5 miles Huntingdon - Godmanchester bypass, from the A1 to Godmanchester, contract was given to A.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] Monk Ltd, of Padgate, on Tuesday 22 May 1973, for £6m.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] Construction began on Monday 4 June 1973, to finish in the summer of 1975.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The local Conservative MP David Renton had played a large part in choosing the route, which not everyone had liked.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The dual-carriageway bypass, from The Stukeleys to Godmanchester, opened as the A604 on Tuesday 30 September 1975.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The Godmanchester to Bar Hill section was built by Sir Alfred McAlpine (Southern), opening in April 1981 as the A604.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The Bar Hill to Swavesey section had opened first, in early December 1980.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] This section had originally been a three-lane single-carriageway road.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The original Fenstanton bypass had opened in early February 1965, as a single carriageway, built by Cementation Company.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The contract for the £350,000 intersection at Bar Hill, was awarded in February 1975 to Roadworks (1952) Ltd, of Ipswich.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The contract for the Girton to Bar Hill section was awarded on Monday 16 February 1976 to Roadworks (1952) Ltd, of Ipswich.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The 9.6-mile A45 Cambridge Northern bypass was accepted by the city council on Thursday 24 June 1971.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The inquiry took place on Tuesday 15 February 1972 at the Guildhall, at the same time as the M11 bypass inquiry.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The inquiry was proceeding in July, and was to take six weeks, but it took six months.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The bypass was to be built by late 1975.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] By May 1974, the bypass was to start in late 1975, and to finish by mid 1977; it would cost £10m in December 1974.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] By September 1975, it was to cost £22m, and to start by January 1976.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The A604 Girton to Bar Hill section was to start at the same time.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] In January 1976, the bypass was to start in April 1976.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] In March 1976, the bypass was to start in June 1976, with a tender accepted by May 1976, to take 18 months.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] In May 1976, the bypass would now open at the end of 1978.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] At the end of June 1976 a £16m contract was given to Bovis Civil Engineering, for the Madingley to Stow cum Quy section.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The start of construction ceremony was held at Madingley on Friday 23 July 1976.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The M11 bypass was to start in mid 1977, to be opened by February 1980.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] At 12pm on Thursday 21 December 1978 the Cambridge northern bypass was opened at Madingley by John Horam; it had taken took 28 months, but the Girton and Madingley interchanges were unfinished, and traffic was allowed late in the evening.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The police were not happy with traffic on such an unfinished road.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] For the 3.75-mile A45 Stow-cum-Quy to Nine Mile Hill section, a one day inquiry was held in April 1975 in Bottisham.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] It was constructed by Monk from September 1976 to be finished by mid-1978, when the northern bypass should be approaching completion.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The 14-mile A45 Newmarket bypass in 1971, was to start in late 1973.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] Wimpey started construction on 6 June 1973, costing £9,047,925.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] Two previous Labour transport secretaries had said that Newmarket did not need a bypass.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The Newmarket bypass opened on Friday 11 July 1975.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The 5.5-mile A45 Seven Mile Bridge to Westley Roundabout section, known as the Kentford bypass, was to start by mid 1975.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] It started in July 1975, and was to finish by July 1977, constructed by Higgs and Hill, costing £3,516,180.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The 3.75-mile A45 Bury bypass in 1971, was to start in early 1972, to be the first section of the new A45 to start.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] It was to start in May 1972, to take 24 months.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] It cost £2,696,230 late April, with the contract given to Monk, to take 18 months.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The Bury bypass was opened at 11.30am on Friday 7 December 1973 by the town MP.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The 9.5-mile A45 Stowmarket-Claydon bypass in 1971, was to start in early 1973, the second section of the new A45 to start.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] Construction started on 29 May 1973 by W. & C.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] It was built in two stages with 7 miles to the A140 at Beacon Hill to open in November 1974, then 3 miles to the A45 at Claydon in November 1975.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] But a lack of steel meant that the first section was eight months late and opened on Thursday 7 August 1975.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The second section opened on Thursday 27 November 1975.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] French civil engineers working on the project, Richard Coult of Rushbrooke, West Suffolk, originally from Felixstowe, died on Turkish Airlines Flight 981 on 3 March 1974; he was one of the 17 players of Bury St Edmunds RUFC on the doomed flight.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The 5-mile (8 km) A45 Rougham to Woolpit Bypass section started in early 1977, costing £4.6 million.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] It was planned to open in January 1979, but opened four months late, due to bad weather.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] It was built by Amey Roadstone Construction (ARC).
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The section opened on Thursday 17 May 1979, which now gave dual carriageway to Ipswich.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The 2.2-mile (3.5 km) A45 Woolpit to Haughley New Street section started in October 1975, built by Monk, costing £1.6 million.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] It would take 21 months to be ready by August 1977.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] One of the main reasons for the widening and the new road was the volume of traffic using the existing road.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] This section was heavily used by local traffic, long-distance traffic to/from the M11 to A1(M), and freight traffic to/from Felixstowe and the Midlands.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] Another reason was the deteriorating condition of the Huntingdon viaduct over the East Coast Main Line.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The viaduct was reaching the end of its life and needed replacing, a task that would require closing the road for a long period of time and not improve congestion.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The Highways Agency unveiled its plans in March 2005.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] Details of the preferred route for the Fen Drayton-to-Fen Ditton section were published in March 2007.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The contract was awarded to Costain Skanska Joint Venture on 28 January 2008, which worked on detailed plans for the Highways Agency before publishing a draft order.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The scheme was expected to open in stages between 2015 and 2016.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The Highways Agency estimated that the widening and the new road would cost in total between £690 million and £1.2 billion, making this the most expensive scheme in its roads programme.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] In October 2009 the cost estimate had risen to £1.3 billion with work due to start in 2012 and being completed in winter 2015/2016.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The Campaign for Better Transport was opposed to the plans, listing their reasons for objection as the carbon emissions the road would induce, the cost, and its negative impact on non-car travel.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The coalition government suspended the scheme when it came into power, with Philip Hammond, the Secretary of State for Transport, suggesting that the scheme would be 'axed', and that the only way it would get built was as a toll road.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] It was confirmed at the end of October that government money would not pay for the scheme, when Roads Minister Mike Penning said that the scheme was not affordable and no longer offered acceptable value for money.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The scheme was officially cancelled in 2010.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] In 2011, the government announced an 'A14 Challenge' inviting people to present proposals for the route.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The revised scheme was similar to its predecessor and was now known as the 'A14 Cambridge to Huntingdon Improvement Scheme'.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] It involved widening of the A1 between Brampton and Alconbury, a new Huntingdon southern bypass, widening of the existing A14 from Swavesey to Milton, and a new local access road between Swavesey and Girton.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The A14 through Huntingdon around the Huntingdon viaduct would be redundant and the viaduct demolished.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] In November 2012, it was reported that the scheme might be back on a fast track to implementation and it was mentioned in the June 2013 spending review.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The project was approved by the Secretary of State for Transport in May 2016.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] Work was due to be completed by March 2021 at a cost of £1.2–1.8 billion.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The works gave rise to one of the largest commercial archaeological projects ever undertaken in the UK.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] In September 2018, Highways England said it was to ask the Planning Inspectorate to consider giving the upgraded section of A14 motorway status, to be known as the A14(M).
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] However, shortly after the amendment of the Development Consent Order, the announcement came that the new Huntingdon southern bypass, between Brampton and the A1 to Swavesey, was ready a year ahead of schedule.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] Instead of waiting for the road to be reclassified, Highways England made the decision to withdraw the application so the road could be opened to traffic as soon as possible.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The 12 miles (19 km) of new bypass opened a year ahead of schedule from the A14 at Swavesey to the A1 at Brampton on 9 December 2019, and the remainder of the route opened on 5 May 2020.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The new route is also to be supplied with variable speed limits to reduce congestion when legislation is passed to allow this technology to be used on primary roads.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] At the same time as the southern section opening, junctions on the A14 between Ellington and Bar Hill were renumbered.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] This upgraded section of the A14 has fewer junctions than previously; junctions 26 to 30 no longer exist.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The section of the old A14 from Godmanchester to the Spittals interchange in Huntingdon was permanently closed after the Huntington bypass opened, in order to remove the Huntingdon viaduct over the East Coast Main Line.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The project to build new links to the town centre is to be completed by 2022.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The construction works of the section between Huntingdon and Godmanchester, specifically where the River Great Ouse is crossed, was painted by Michael Murfin, a local artist.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The artist's work records various stages of the build, depicting workers on the site and the heavy machinery used in the construction of the viaduct.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The numbering of the A14 is inconsistent with the national road numbering scheme, as it begins in zone 5 and crosses through zone 6 on the way to zone 1 east of Huntingdon to Felixstowe.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The road is concurrent with the A12 road from the Seven Hills Interchange to the Copdock Interchange which forms the Ipswich Southern bypass and with the A11 road between junctions 36 and 38.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] From the A12 west of Ipswich to the M1/M6 junction, the A14 is part of (but not signed as) the E-road E 24, and from Ipswich to Felixstowe it is part of E 30.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] East of the Girton Interchange with the M11 at Cambridge, the A14 used to be the A45, and much of the long-distance traffic further west had previously used the A45 route.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The section between Cambridge and Kettering used to be the A604, apart from a short section near Kettering that used to be part of the A6.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The road which was the A14 until the late 1980s is now the A1198 between Royston, Hertfordshire and Godmanchester.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] Until the opening in 2019 of the Huntingdon bypass, there was some confusion as to the identity of the section of road between the A141 junction at Stukeley (Spittals Interchange) and the A1(M).
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The Ordnance Survey 1:25000 map showed the A-road section as part of the A14 and the motorway section (between the B1043 junction and the A1(M)) as the A14(M).
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] However, some official documents, including the 1993 statutory instrument which authorised the motorway upgrade, referred to it as the A604(M).
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The same confusion appeared on the former Highways Agency page about the 1996-8 upgrade to the A1(M) between Alconbury and Peterborough.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The signs on entering the motorway section, unusually, show a large "start of motorway" symbol with no number, and there are no driver location signs confirming the route number.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] Following the opening of the Huntingdon bypass, the former A14 between the A1(M) and the Cambridge Services at Swavesey has been renumbered A1307, with the section through Huntingdon itself closed for the time being.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] Therefore, the "Alconbury spur" of the former A14 trunk route finally carries a unique road number again, in the form of the A1307.
[src:archaeology/a14-road-england] The Highways Agency has plans to increase capacity from junction 3 to junction 10 near Kettering 'in the longer term' and also to widen the road throughout Northamptonshire to "help cut the number of accidents and cope with the likely growth in traffic".
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Abductive reasoning, unlike deductive reasoning, yields a plausible conclusion but does not definitively verify it.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Abductive conclusions do not eliminate uncertainty or doubt, which is expressed in terms such as "best available" or "most likely".
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] While inductive reasoning draws general conclusions that apply to many situations, abductive conclusions are confined to the particular observations in question.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] In the 1990s, as computing power grew, the fields of law, computer science, and artificial intelligence research spurred renewed interest in the subject of abduction.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Diagnostic expert systems frequently employ abduction.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Deductive reasoning allows deriving b from a only where b is a formal logical consequence of a .
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] In other words, deduction derives the consequences of the assumed.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Given the truth of the assumptions, a valid deduction guarantees the truth of the conclusion.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] For example, given that "Socrates is a man" ( $a_{1}$ ) and "All men are mortal" ( $a_{2}$ ), it follows that "Socrates is mortal" ( b ).
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Inductive reasoning is the process of inferring some *general* principle b from a body of knowledge a , where b does not necessarily follow from a . a might give us very good reason to accept b but does not ensure b .
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] For example, if all swans that a person has observed so far are white, they may infer a universal categorical proposition of the form *All swans are white*.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] They have good reason to believe the conclusion from the premise because it is the *best explanation* for their observations, but the truth of the conclusion is not guaranteed.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Indeed, it turns out that some swans are black.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Abductive reasoning allows inferring a as an explanation of b .
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] As a result of this inference, abduction allows the precondition a to be abducted from the consequence b .
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Deductive reasoning and abductive reasoning differ in which end, left or right, of the proposition " a entails b " serves as the conclusion.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] For example, with deductive reasoning, knowing that it rained heavily during the night, you could deduce that the lawn will be wet in the morning without looking outside.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] With abductive reasoning, a couple leaving their house in the morning and seeing that their lawn is wet might abduce that it rained while they were asleep.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] This serves as a hypothesis that "best explains" their observation.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Given the many possible explanations for the lawn getting wet, their abduction does not establish certainty that it rained overnight, but it is still useful and can serve to orient them in their surroundings.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Despite many possible explanations for any physical process we observe, we tend to abduce a single explanation (or a few) for this process in the expectation that we can better orient ourselves in our surroundings and disregard some possibilities.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Properly used, abductive reasoning can be a useful source of priors in Bayesian statistics.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] One can understand abductive reasoning as inference to the best explanation, although the terms *abduction* and *inference to the best explanation* are not always used equivalently.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] In logic, explanation is accomplished through the use of a logical theory T representing a domain and a set of observations O .
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Abduction is the process of deriving a set of explanations of O according to T and picking out one of those explanations.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] In formal logic, O and E are assumed to be sets of literals.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Among the possible explanations E satisfying these two conditions, some other condition of minimality is usually imposed to avoid irrelevant facts (not contributing to the entailment of O ) being included in the explanations.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Abduction is then the process that picks out some member of E .
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Criteria for picking out a member representing "the best" explanation include the simplicity, the prior probability, or the explanatory power of the explanation.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] A proof-theoretical abduction method for first-order classical logic based on the sequent calculus and a dual one, based on semantic tableaux (analytic tableaux) have been proposed.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] The methods are sound and complete and work for full first-order logic, without requiring any preliminary reduction of formulae into normal forms.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] These methods have also been extended to modal logic.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Abductive logic programming is a computational framework that extends normal logic programming with abduction.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] It separates the theory T into two components, one of which is a normal logic program, used to generate E by means of backward reasoning, the other of which is a set of integrity constraints, used to filter the set of candidate explanations.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] A different formalization of abduction is based on inverting the function that calculates the visible effects of the hypotheses.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Formally, we are given a set of hypotheses H and a set of manifestations M ; they are related by the domain knowledge, represented by a function e that takes as an argument a set of hypotheses and gives as a result the corresponding set of manifestations.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] In other words, for every subset of the hypotheses $H'\subseteq H$ , their effects are known to be $e(H')$ .
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Abduction is performed by finding a set $H'\subseteq H$ such that $M\subseteq e(H')$ .
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] In other words, abduction is performed by finding a set of hypotheses $H'$ such that their effects $e(H')$ include all observations M .
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] A common assumption is that the effects of the hypotheses are independent, that is, for every $H'\subseteq H$ , it holds that $e(H')=\bigcup _{h\in H'}e(\{h\})$ .
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] If this condition is met, abduction can be seen as a form of set covering.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Abductive validation is the process of validating a given hypothesis through abductive reasoning.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] This can also be called reasoning through successive approximation.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Under this principle, an explanation is valid if it is the best possible explanation of a set of known data.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] The best possible explanation is often defined in terms of simplicity and elegance (see Occam's razor).
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Subjective logic generalises probabilistic logic by including degrees of epistemic uncertainty in the input arguments, i.e. instead of probabilities, the analyst can express arguments as subjective opinions.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Abduction in subjective logic is thus a generalization of probabilistic abduction described above.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] The input arguments in subjective logic are subjective opinions which can be binomial when the opinion applies to a binary variable or multinomial when it applies to an *n*-ary variable.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Assume the domains $\mathbf {X}$ and $\mathbf {Y}$ with respective variables X and Y , the set of conditional opinions $\omega _{X\mid Y}$ (i.e. one conditional opinion for each value y ), and the base rate distribution $a_{Y}$ .
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Using these inverted conditionals together with the opinion $\omega _{X}$ subjective deduction denoted by the operator $\circledcirc$ can be used to abduce the marginal opinion $\omega _{Y\,{\overline {\|}}\,X}$ .
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] The symbolic notation for subjective abduction is " ${\widetilde {\|}}$ ", and the operator itself is denoted as " ${\widetilde {\circledcirc }}$ ".
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] The operator for the subjective Bayes' theorem is denoted " ${\widetilde {\phi \,}}$ ", and subjective deduction is denoted " $\circledcirc$ ".
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] The advantage of using subjective logic abduction compared to probabilistic abduction is that both aleatoric and epistemic uncertainty about the input argument probabilities can be explicitly expressed and taken into account during the analysis.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] It is thus possible to perform abductive analysis in the presence of uncertain arguments, which naturally results in degrees of uncertainty in the output conclusions.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] The idea that the simplest, most easily verifiable solution should be preferred over its more complicated counterparts is a very old one.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] To this point, George Pólya, in his treatise on problem-solving, makes reference to the following Latin truism: *simplex sigillum veri* (simplicity is the seal of truth).
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] The American philosopher Charles Sanders Peirce introduced abduction into modern logic.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Over the years he called such inference *hypothesis*, *abduction*, *presumption*, and *retroduction*.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] He considered it a topic in logic as a normative field in philosophy, not in purely formal or mathematical logic, and eventually as a topic also in economics of research.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] As two stages of the development, extension, etc., of a hypothesis in scientific inquiry, abduction and also induction are often collapsed into one overarching concept—the hypothesis.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] That is why, in the scientific method known from Galileo and Bacon, the abductive stage of hypothesis formation is conceptualized simply as induction.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Thus, in the twentieth century this collapse was reinforced by Karl Popper's explication of the hypothetico-deductive model, where the hypothesis is considered to be just "a guess" (in the spirit of Peirce).
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] However, when the formation of a hypothesis is considered the result of a process it becomes clear that this "guess" has already been tried and made more robust in thought as a necessary stage of its acquiring the status of hypothesis.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Indeed, many abductions are rejected or heavily modified by subsequent abductions before they ever reach this stage.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Before 1900, Peirce treated abduction as the use of a known rule to explain an observation.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] For instance: it is a known rule that, if it rains, grass gets wet; so, to explain the fact that the grass on this lawn is wet, one *abduces* that it has rained.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Abduction can lead to false conclusions if other rules that might explain the observation are not taken into account—e.g. the grass could be wet from dew.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] This remains the common use of the term "abduction" in the social sciences and in artificial intelligence.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Peirce consistently characterized it as the kind of inference that originates a hypothesis by concluding in an explanation, though an unassured one, for some very curious or surprising (anomalous) observation stated in a premise.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] As early as 1865 he wrote that all conceptions of cause and force are reached through hypothetical inference; in the 1900s he wrote that all explanatory content of theories is reached through abduction.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] In other respects Peirce revised his view of abduction over the years.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] In Peirce's *On the Natural Classification of Arguments* (1867), hypothetical inference always deals with a cluster of characters (call them *P′, P′′, P′′′,* etc.) known to occur at least whenever a certain character (*M*) occurs.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Note that categorical syllogisms have elements traditionally called middles, predicates, and subjects.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] For example: All *men* [middle] are *mortal* [predicate]; *Socrates* [subject] is a *man* [middle]; ergo *Socrates* [subject] is *mortal* [predicate]".
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Below, 'M' stands for a middle; 'P' for a predicate; 'S' for a subject.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Peirce held that all deduction can be put into the form of the categorical syllogism Barbara (AAA-1).
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] In 1878, in *Deduction, Induction, and Hypothesis*, there is no longer a need for multiple characters or predicates in order for an inference to be hypothetical, although it is still helpful.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Moreover, Peirce no longer poses hypothetical inference as concluding in a *probable* hypothesis.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] In the forms themselves, it is understood but not explicit that induction involves random selection and that hypothetical inference involves response to a "very curious circumstance".
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] The forms instead emphasize the modes of inference as rearrangements of one another's propositions (without the bracketed hints shown below).
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Peirce long treated abduction in terms of induction from characters or traits (weighed, not counted like objects), explicitly so in his influential 1883 "A theory of probable inference", in which he returns to involving probability in the hypothetical conclusion.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Like *Deduction, Induction, and Hypothesis* in 1878, it was widely read (see the historical books on statistics by Stephen Stigler), unlike his later amendments of his conception of abduction.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Today abduction remains most commonly understood as induction from characters and extension of a known rule to cover unexplained circumstances.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Sherlock Holmes used this method of reasoning in the stories of Arthur Conan Doyle, although Holmes refers to it as "deductive reasoning".
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] In 1902 Peirce wrote that he now regarded the syllogistical forms and the doctrine of extension and comprehension (i.e., objects and characters as referenced by terms), as being less fundamental than he had earlier thought.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] The hypothesis is framed, but not asserted, in a premise, then asserted as rationally suspectable in the conclusion.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Thus, as in the earlier categorical syllogistic form, the conclusion is formulated from some premise(s).
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] But all the same the hypothesis consists more clearly than ever in a new or outside idea beyond what is known or observed.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Induction in a sense goes beyond observations already reported in the premises, but it merely amplifies ideas already known to represent occurrences, or tests an idea supplied by hypothesis; either way it requires previous abductions in order to get such ideas in the first place.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Induction seeks facts to test a hypothesis; abduction seeks a hypothesis to account for facts.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Note that the hypothesis ("A") could be of a rule.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] It need not even be a rule strictly necessitating the surprising observation ("C"), which needs to follow only as a "matter of course"; or the "course" itself could amount to some known rule, merely alluded to, and also not necessarily a rule of strict necessity.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Peirce did not remain quite convinced about any such form as the categorical syllogistic form or the 1903 form.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] In 1911, he wrote, "I do not, at present, feel quite convinced that any logical form can be assigned that will cover all 'Retroductions'.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] It is a method for fruitful clarification of conceptions by equating the meaning of a conception with the conceivable practical implications of its object's conceived effects.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Peirce held that that is precisely tailored to abduction's purpose in inquiry, the forming of an idea that could conceivably shape informed conduct.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] In various writings in the 1900s he said that the conduct of abduction (or retroduction) is governed by considerations of economy, belonging in particular to the economics of research.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] He regarded economics as a normative science whose analytic portion might be part of logical methodeutic (that is, theory of inquiry).
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Logical critic, or logic proper, on validity or justifiability of inference, the conditions for true representation.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Critique of arguments in their various modes (deduction, induction, abduction).
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Methodeutic, or speculative rhetoric, on the conditions for determination of interpretations.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Methodology of inquiry in its interplay of modes.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Peirce had, from the start, seen the modes of inference as being coordinated together in scientific inquiry and, by the 1900s, held that hypothetical inference in particular is inadequately treated at the level of critique of arguments.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] To increase the assurance of a hypothetical conclusion, one needs to deduce implications about evidence to be found, predictions which induction can test through observation so as to evaluate the hypothesis.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] That is Peirce's outline of the scientific method of inquiry, as covered in his inquiry methodology, which includes pragmatism or, as he later called it, pragmaticism, the clarification of ideas in terms of their conceivable implications regarding informed practice.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Induction is inference through an *index* (a sign by factual connection); a sample is an index of the totality from which it is drawn.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Deduction is inference through a *symbol* (a sign by interpretive habit irrespective of resemblance or connection to its object).
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] At the critical level Peirce examined the forms of abductive arguments (as discussed above), and came to hold that the hypothesis should economize explanation for plausibility in terms of the feasible and natural.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] In 1908 Peirce described this plausibility in some detail.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] The phrase "inference to the best explanation" (not used by Peirce but often applied to hypothetical inference) is not always understood as referring to the most simple and natural hypotheses (such as those with the fewest assumptions).
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] However, in other senses of "best", such as "standing up best to tests", it is hard to know which is the best explanation to form, since one has not tested it yet.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Still, for Peirce, any justification of an abductive inference as "good" is not completed upon its formation as an argument (unlike with induction and deduction) and instead depends also on its methodological role and promise (such as its testability) in advancing inquiry.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Here, considerations such as probability, absent from the treatment of abduction at the critical level, come into play.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Peirce indicated that abductive reasoning is driven by the need for "economy in research"—the expected fact-based productivity of hypotheses, prior to deductive and inductive processes of verification.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] A key concept proposed by him in this regard is "uberty"—the expected fertility and pragmatic value of reasoning.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] This concept seems to be gaining support via association to the Free Energy Principle.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Gilbert Harman was a professor of philosophy at Princeton University.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Harman's 1965 account of the role of "inference to the best explanation" – inferring the existence of that which we need for the best explanation of observable phenomena – has been very influential.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Stephen Jay Gould, in answering the Omphalos hypothesis, claimed that only hypotheses that can be proved incorrect lie within the domain of science and only these hypotheses are good explanations of facts worth inferring to.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Applications in artificial intelligence include fault diagnosis, belief revision, and automated planning.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] The most direct application of abduction is that of automatically detecting faults in systems: given a theory relating faults with their effects and a set of observed effects, abduction can be used to derive sets of faults that are likely to be the cause of the problem.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] In medicine, abduction can be seen as a component of clinical evaluation and judgment.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] The Internist-I diagnostic system, the first AI system that covered the field of Internal Medicine, used abductive reasoning to converge on the most likely causes of a set of patient symptoms that it acquired through an interactive dialog with an expert user.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Abduction can also be used to model automated planning.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Given a logical theory relating action occurrences with their effects (for example, a formula of the event calculus), the problem of finding a plan for reaching a state can be modeled as the problem of abducting a set of literals implying that the final state is the goal state.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] In intelligence analysis, analysis of competing hypotheses and Bayesian networks, probabilistic abductive reasoning is used extensively.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Similarly in medical diagnosis and legal reasoning, the same methods are being used, although there have been many examples of errors, especially caused by the base rate fallacy and the prosecutor's fallacy.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Belief revision, the process of adapting beliefs in view of new information, is another field in which abduction has been applied.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] The main problem of belief revision is that the new information may be inconsistent with the prior web of beliefs, while the result of the incorporation cannot be inconsistent.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] The process of updating the web of beliefs can be done by the use of abduction: once an explanation for the observation has been found, integrating it does not generate inconsistency.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] In 1992 Peter Gärdenfors presented a paper which contained a brief survey of the area of belief revision and its relation to updating of logical databases, and explores the relationship between belief revision and nonmonotonic logic.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] This use of abduction is not straightforward, as adding propositional formulae to other propositional formulae can only make inconsistencies worse.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Instead, abduction is done at the level of the ordering of preference of the possible worlds.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Preference models use fuzzy logic or utility models.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] In the philosophy of science, abduction has been the key inference method to support scientific realism, and much of the debate about scientific realism is focused on whether abduction is an acceptable method of inference.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] In historical linguistics, abduction during language acquisition is often taken to be an essential part of processes of language change such as reanalysis and analogy.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] In applied linguistics research, abductive reasoning is starting to be used as an alternative explanation to inductive reasoning, in recognition of anticipated outcomes of qualitative inquiry playing a role in shaping the direction of analysis.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] It is defined as "The use of an unclear premise based on observations, pursuing theories to try to explain it" (Rose et al., 2020, p.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Abduction is used as the mechanism for getting from art to agency.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] That is, abduction can explain how works of art inspire a *sensus communis:* the commonly held views shared by members that characterize a given society.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Abduction is the answer to this conundrum because the tentative nature of the abduction concept (Peirce likened it to guessing) means that not only can it operate outside of any pre-existing framework, but moreover, it can actually intimate the existence of a framework.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] As Gell reasons in his analysis, the physical existence of the artwork prompts the viewer to perform an abduction that imbues the artwork with intentionality.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] A statue of a goddess, for example, in some senses actually becomes the goddess in the mind of the beholder; and represents not only the form of the deity but also her intentions (which are adduced from the feeling of her very presence).
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Therefore, through abduction, Gell claims that art can have the kind of agency that plants the seeds that grow into cultural myths.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] The power of agency is the power to motivate actions and inspire ultimately the shared understanding that characterizes any given society.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] In formal methods, logic is used to specify and prove properties of computer programs.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] Abduction has been used in mechanized reasoning tools to increase the level of automation of the proof activity.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] It led to a program-proof startup company, which was acquired by Facebook, and the Infer program analysis tool, which led to thousands of bugs being prevented in industrial codebases.
[src:archaeology/abductive-reasoning] In addition to inference of function preconditions, abduction has been used to automate inference of invariants for program loops, inference of specifications of unknown code, and in synthesis of the programs themselves.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] The science of abnormal psychology studies two types of behaviors: adaptive and maladaptive behaviors.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Maladaptive behaviors suggest that some problem(s) exist and can also imply that the individual is vulnerable and unable to cope with environmental stress, leading to difficulties functioning in daily life across emotions, thinking, physical actions, and speech.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Adaptive behaviors are well-suited to the nature of people, their lifestyles and surroundings, and the people they communicate with, allowing them to understand each other.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Clinical psychology is the applied field of psychology that seeks to assess, understand, and treat psychological conditions in clinical practice.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] The theoretical field known as *abnormal psychology* may form a backdrop to such work.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Still, clinical psychologists in the field are unlikely to use the term 'abnormal' in reference to their practice.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Psychopathology is a similar term to abnormal psychology, but may have more of an implication of an underlying pathology (disease process), which assumes the medical model of mental disturbance and as such, is a term more commonly used in the medical specialty known as psychiatry.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Hippocrates (460–377 BCE) hypothesized that the body and mind become unwell when the so-called humors, vital fluids in the body, become unbalanced.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] The four temperaments theory posits four such humors: black bile, yellow bile, phlegm, and blood.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Each humor was associated with a particular temperament: too much phlegm causes a person to be fatigued, too much black bile causes melancholia, yellow bile causes a quick temper, and too much blood causes optimism, cheerfulness, and confidence.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] The act of placing individuals with mental illness in a separate facility known as an asylum dates to 1547, when King Henry VIII of England established the St.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] This hospital, nicknamed Bedlam, was famous for its deplorable conditions.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Asylums remained popular throughout the Middle Ages and the Renaissance era.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] These early asylums often had miserable conditions.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Patients were seen as a "burden" to society, locked away and treated almost like beasts to be dealt with, rather than patients needing treatment.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] However, many of the patients received helpful medical treatment.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] There was scientific curiosity into abnormal behavior, although it was rarely investigated in the early asylums.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Inmates in these early asylums were often put on display for profit, as they were viewed as less than human.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] The early asylums were basically modifications of the existing criminal institutions.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] In the late 18th century, the idea of humane treatment for patients gained favor due to the work of Philippe Pinel in France.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] He pushed for the idea that the patients should be treated with kindness, and not the cruelty inflicted on them, as if they were animals or criminals.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] His experimental ideas, such as removing the chains from the patients, were met with reluctance.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] The experiments in kindness proved a great success, helping reform how mental institutions would be run.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Institutionalization would continue to improve throughout the 19th and 20th centuries, as a result of the work of many humanitarians such as Dorothea Dix and the mental hygiene movement, which promoted the physical well-being of people with mental health conditions.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] "Dix, more than any other figure in the nineteenth century, made people in America and virtually all of Europe aware that the insane were being subjected to incredible abuses." Through this movement, millions of dollars were raised to build new institutions to house the mentally ill.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Mental hospitals grew substantially in number during the 20th century as care for the mentally ill increased.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] By 1939, there were over 400,000 patients in state mental hospitals in the US.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Hospital stays were normally quite long for the patients, with some individuals being treated for many years.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] These hospitals, while better than the asylums of the past, still lacked the means to provide effective treatment for patients.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Even though the reform movement had occurred, patients were often still met with cruel and inhumane treatment.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Things began to change in 1946, when Mary Jane Ward published the influential novel *The Snake Pit*, which was adapted into a popular movie of the same name.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] The book called attention to the conditions that people with a mental health condition faced, and helped to spark concern in the general public to create more humane mental health care in these overcrowded hospitals.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] That same year, the National Institute of Mental Health was also created, providing support for training hospital employees and research into patients' conditions.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] During this period, the Hill–Burton Act was also passed, a program that funded mental health hospitals.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Along with the Community Health Services Act of 1963, the Hill–Burton Acts helped create outpatient psychiatric clinics, inpatient general hospitals, and rehabilitation and community consultation centers.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] In the late twentieth century, however, many mental hospitals were closed in many countries.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] In England, for example, only 14 of the 130 psychiatric institutions established in the early 20th century remained open at the start of the 21st century.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Kennedy launched the community health movement in the United States as a "bold new approach" to mental health care, aimed at coordinating mental health services for citizens in mental health centers.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Over the span of 40 years, the United States saw about a 90 percent drop in the number of patients in psychiatric hospitals.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Deinstitutionalisation ended the long-term confinement of patients in isolating mental hospitals, which could and did cause long-term negative adaptations.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] For instance, institutionalizing people with schizophrenia worsens negative symptoms.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] However, the practice is sometimes criticised for a perceived rise in homelessness amongst people who were previously institutionalized, or are presumed to have been in the institution era.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] People have tried to explain and control abnormal behavior for thousands of years.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Historically, there have been three main approaches to abnormal behavior: the supernatural, biological, and psychological traditions.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Abnormal psychology revolves around two major paradigms for explaining mental disorders, the *psychological* paradigm and the *biological* paradigm.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] The psychological paradigm focuses more on the humanistic, cognitive, and behavioral causes and effects of psychopathology.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] The biological paradigm includes theories that focus more on physical factors, such as genetics and neurochemistry.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] In the first supernatural tradition, also known as the demonological method, abnormal behavior is attributed to agents outside the human body.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] According to this model, abnormal behaviors are caused by demons, aliens, or spirits, or the influences of the Moon, planets, and stars.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] During the Stone Age, trepanning was performed on those who had mental illness, to literally cut the evil spirits out of the victim's head.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Conversely, Ancient Chinese, Ancient Egyptians, and Hebrews believed that these were evil demons or spirits and advocated exorcism.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] By the time of the Greeks and Romans, mental illnesses were thought to be caused by an imbalance of the four humors, which led to treatments such as draining fluids from the brain.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] During the Medieval period, many Europeans believed that the power of witches, demons, and spirits caused abnormal behaviors.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] People with psychological disorders were thought to be possessed by evil spirits that had to be exorcised through religious rituals.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] If exorcism failed, some authorities advocated steps such as confinement, beating, and other types of torture to make the body uninhabitable to witches, demons, and spirits.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] The belief that witches, demons, and spirits were responsible for abnormal behavior persisted into the 15th century.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Swiss alchemist, astrologer, and physician Paracelsus (1493–1541), on the other hand, rejected the idea that abnormal behaviors were caused by witches, demons, and spirits and suggested that the movements of the moon and stars influenced people's mind and behaviors.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Some people, especially in developing countries, as well as some followers of religious sects in developed countries, continue to believe that supernatural powers influence human behavior.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] In Western academia, the supernatural tradition has been largely replaced by the biological and psychological traditions.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Throughout history, societies have proposed several explanations for abnormal human behavior.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] In some hunter-gatherer societies, animists have believed that people exhibiting abnormal behavior are possessed by malevolent spirits.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] This idea has been associated with trepanation, the practice of cutting a hole into the individual's skull to release the malevolent spirits.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Although it has been difficult to define abnormal psychology, one definition includes characteristics such as statistical infrequency.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] A more formalized response to spiritual beliefs about abnormality is the practice of exorcism.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Performed by religious authorities, exorcism is thought of as another way to release evil spirits who cause pathological behavior within the person.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] In some instances, individuals exhibiting unusual thoughts or behaviors have been exiled from society, or worse.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Perceived witchcraft, for example, has been punished by death.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Two Catholic Inquisitors wrote the *Malleus Maleficarum* (Latin for "The Hammer Against Witches"), which many Inquisitors and witch-hunters used.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] It contained an early taxonomy of perceived deviant behavior and proposed guidelines for prosecuting deviant individuals.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] In the biological tradition, psychological disorders are attributed to biological causes.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] In the psychological tradition, disorders are attributed to faulty psychological development, and to social context.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] The medical or biological perspective holds the belief that most or all abnormal behavior can be attributed to a medical factor; assuming all psychological disorders are diseases.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] The Greek physician Hippocrates, considered the father of Western medicine, played a major role in the biological tradition.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Hippocrates and his associates wrote the Hippocratic Corpus between 450 and 350 BC, in which they suggested that abnormal behaviors can be treated like any other disease.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Hippocrates viewed the brain as the seat of consciousness, emotion, intelligence, and wisdom, and believed that disorders involving these functions would logically be located there.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] These ideas of Hippocrates and his associates were later adopted by Galen, the Roman physician.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Galen extended these ideas and developed a strong and influential school of thought within the biological tradition that extended well into the 18th century.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Kendra Cherry, MSEd, states: "The medical approach to abnormal psychology focuses on the biological causes of mental illness.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] This perspective emphasizes understanding the underlying cause of disorders, which might include genetic inheritance, related physical disorders, infections, and chemical imbalances.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] According to Sigmund Freud's structural model, the id, ego, and superego are three theoretical constructs that define the way an individual interacts with the external world, as well as responding to internal forces The Id represents the instinctual drives of an individual that remain unconscious.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] The superego represents a person's conscience and their internalization of societal norms and morality.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Finally, the ego serves to realistically integrate the id's drives with the superego's prohibitions.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Lack of development in the superego, or an incoherently developed Superego within an individual, will result in thoughts and actions that are irrational and abnormal, contrary to the norms and beliefs of society.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Unconscious fears drive irrational beliefs and can result in abnormal behavior.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Rational emotive behavior therapy helps to drive irrational and maladaptive beliefs out of one's mind.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] The term sociocultural refers to the various circles of influence on the individual, ranging from close friends and family to the institutions and policies of a country or the world as a whole.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Discriminations, whether based on social class, income, race and ethnicity, or gender, can influence the development of abnormal behaviour.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] The number of different theoretical perspectives in the field of psychological abnormality has made it difficult to explain psychopathology properly.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] The attempt to explain all mental disorders with the same theory leads to reductionism (explaining a disorder or other complex phenomena using only a single idea or perspective).
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Most mental disorders are composed of several factors, which is why one must take into account several theoretical perspectives when attempting to diagnose or explain a particular behavioral abnormality or mental disorder.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Explaining mental disorders with a combination of theoretical perspectives is known as multiple causality.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] The diathesis–stress model emphasizes the importance of applying multiple causality to psychopathology, by stressing that both precipitating causes and predisposing causes cause disorders.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] A precipitating cause is an immediate trigger that instigates a person's action or behavior.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] A predisposing cause is an underlying factor that interacts with the immediate factors to result in a disorder.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Both causes play a key role in the development of a psychological disorder.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] For example, high neuroticism antedates most types of psychopathology.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] There is a wide range of mental disorders that are considered to be forms of Abnormal Psychology.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Schizophrenia can be described as a disorder that causes extreme loss of touch with reality.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] The Psychotic nature of schizophrenia manifests itself through delusions, as well as auditory and visual hallucinations.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Schizophrenia is known to have a genetic etiology, as well as other biological components, such as brain disruptions in the prenatal development period.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Attention deficit hyperactivity disorder (ADHD) is characterized by high amounts of inattention and hyperactive impulsiveness.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Inattentive symptoms include not listening, careless errors, disorganization, losing personal belongings, becoming easily distracted, and forgetfulness.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Symptoms of hyperactive impulsiveness include fidgeting, talking excessively, and interrupting others.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Antisocial personality disorder is a cluster of personality traits that lead to specific outcomes and violate others' rights.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] These personality traits include callousness, deceitfulness, lack of remorse, apathy, manipulation of others, impulsiveness, and grandiosity.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Additional traits may include superficial charm, sexual promiscuity, and pathological lying.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Dissociative identity disorder (DID) involves one individual having multiple personalities.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Those with DID are described as having multiple selves that each have their own consciousness and awareness.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] DID has two main etiologies, which are the post-traumatic and socio-cognitive models.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] The post-traumatic model states that DID is caused by inescapable past trauma, such as child abuse.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] The child dissociates and forms alternate personalities as a coping mechanism in response to the current trauma.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Even when the trauma ends, the personalities continue to disrupt the person's life long-term.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] The socio-cognitive model states that people implicitly act as if they have multiple personalities to align with cultural norms.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Those with social anxiety disorder (SAD) have a very intense fear of social situations.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] This fear stems from the belief that the person will be evaluated negatively or embarrass themselves.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] SAD is also considered to be one of the more disabling mental disorders.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Symptoms of this disorder include fear in most, if not all, social situations.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] SAD can develop after a traumatic and/or embarrassing experience has occurred while other people were observing the person.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Generalized anxiety disorder is characterized by a constant, chronic state of worry and anxiety that is related to a large variety of situations and is difficult to control.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Additional symptoms may include irritability, fatigue, concentration difficulties, and restlessness.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Individuals with specific phobias have an extreme fear and avoidance of various objects or situations.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Specifically, fears become phobias when there is excessive and unreasonable fear that is disproportionate to the culture that the individual is in.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Examples of specific phobias include, but are not limited to, phobias of school, blood, injury, needles, small animals, and heights.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Post-traumatic stress disorder (PTSD) is described as physical and mental distress related to past traumatic experiences.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] PTSD can manifest a large variety of symptoms, including, but not limited to, nightmares, flashbacks, avoidance, and/or physiological reactions related to stimuli regarding the trauma, shame, guilt, anger, hypervigilance, and social withdrawal.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] PTSD symptoms can arise due to various experiences that involve actual or threatened violence, injury, or death.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Firsthand experience, witnessing, or learning about traumatic experiences can lead to the development of PTSD.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] The DSM-5 is the manual that contains the most widely discussed and researched information on this topic.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Various conditions have been included in this manual and continue to be added to the DSM-5.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] The causes of many of these diseases stem from genetic, biological, sociocultural, systemic, and biopsychosocial factors.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Various counseling theories support and help explain the findings related to each illness.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] In North America, this is the Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of the American Psychiatric Association.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] The current version of the book is known as the DSM-5.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] It lists a set of disorders and provides detailed descriptions of what constitutes a mental disorder.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] The DSM-5 identifies three key elements that must be present to constitute a mental disorder.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] The DSM-5 uses three main sections to organize its contents.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Section I includes the introduction, use, and basics of the DSM-5.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Section II includes diagnostic criteria and codes.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Section III includes emerging measures and models.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Section I of the DSM-5 briefly prefaces purpose, content, structure, and use.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] This includes basics, introductions, and cautionary statements for forensic use.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Information is also given about the revision and review processes as well as the DSM-5's goals to harmonize with the ICD-11.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] An explanation regarding the change from the previous multi-axial classification system to the current three-section system is also included here.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Section II of the DSM-5 contains a wide range of diagnostic criteria and codes used to establish and diagnose a vast array of abnormal psychological constructs.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] These categories are used to organize abnormal psychological concepts based on their similarities.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Section III of the DSM-5 contains the various methods and strategies that are used to make clinical decisions, understand culture, and explore emerging diagnoses.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] The major international nosologic system for the classification of mental disorders is the International Classification of Diseases, 10th revision (ICD-10).
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] The ICD-10 has been used by World Health Organization (WHO) Member States since 1994.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Chapter five covers some 300 mental and behavioral disorders.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] The APA's DSM-IV has influenced Chapter 5 of ICD-10, and there is a great deal of concordance between the two.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Beginning in January 2022, the ICD-11 will replace the ICD-10 in WHO member states.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] WHO maintains free access to the ICD-10 Online.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] The ICD-11 is the most recent version of the International Classification of Diseases.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] The *Mental, behavioral, or Neurodevelopmental disorders section* highlights forms of abnormal psychology.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Psychologists may use different perspectives to gain a better understanding of abnormal psychology.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Some of them may concentrate on a single perspective.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] But professionals prefer to combine two or three perspectives to obtain meaningful information for better treatments.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Psychoanalytic theory is heavily based on the theory of the neurologist Sigmund Freud.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] These ideas often represented repressed emotions and memories from a patient's childhood in the patient's unconscious.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] According to psychoanalytic theory, these repressions cause the disturbances people experience in their daily lives, and by finding their source, one should be able to eliminate them.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] This is accomplished through a variety of methods, including free association, hypnosis, and insight.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] The goal of these methods is to induce a catharsis, or emotional release, in the patient, which should indicate that the source of the problem has been tapped and can then be treated.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Freud's psychosexual stages also played a key role in this form of therapy, as he would often believe that the problems the patient was experiencing were due to them becoming stuck, or "fixated", in a particular stage.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Dreams also played a major role in this form of therapy, as Freud viewed dreams as a way to gain insight into the unconscious mind.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Patients were often asked to keep dream journals to bring in for discussion during the next therapy session.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] There are many potential problems associated with this style of therapy, including resistance to the repressed memory or feeling, and negative transference onto the therapist.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Psychoanalysis was carried on by many after Freud, including his daughter Anna Freud, and Jacques Lacan.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Many others have also elaborated on Freud's original theory and added their own take on defense mechanisms or dream analysis.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] While psychoanalysis has fallen out of favor to more modern forms of therapy, it is still used by some clinical psychologists to varying degrees.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Behavior therapy relies on the principles of behaviorism, such as involving classical and operant conditioning.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Behaviorism arose in the early 20th century, from the work of psychologists such as James Watson and B.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Behaviorism states that all behaviors humans do are because of a stimulus and reinforcement.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] While this reinforcement is normally for good behavior, it can also occur for maladaptive behavior.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] In this therapeutic view, the patient's maladaptive behavior has been reinforced, which will lead to its repetition.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] The goal of the therapy is to reinforce less maladaptive behaviors so that, over time, these adaptive behaviors become the patient's primary ones.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Humanistic therapy aims to achieve self-actualization (Carl Rogers, 1961).
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] In this style of therapy, the therapist will focus on the patient themselves rather than on the patient's problem.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] The goal of this therapy is, by treating the patient as "human", rather than "client", to get to the source of the problem and to resolve the problem effectively.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Humanistic therapy has been on the rise in recent years and is associated with numerous benefits.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] It is considered one of the core elements needed for therapeutic effectiveness and a significant contributor to the well-being of not only the patient but society as a whole.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Some say that all therapeutic approaches today draw on the humanistic approach in some way, and that humanistic therapy is the best way to treat a patient.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Humanistic therapy can be used on people of all ages; it is very popular among children in its variant known as "play therapy".
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Cognitive behavioural therapy (CBT) aims to influence thought and cognition (Beck, 1977).
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] This form of therapy relies on not only the components of behavioral therapy as mentioned before, but also the elements of cognitive psychology.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] This relies on not only the clients behavioral problems that could have arisen from conditioning, but also their negative schemas and distorted perceptions of the world around them.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] These negative schemas may cause distress in the patient's life; for example, they may lead to unrealistic expectations about how well they should perform at work or how they should look.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] When these expectations are not met, it will often result in maladaptive behaviors, such as depression, obsessive compulsions, and anxiety.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] With CBT, the goal is to change the schemas causing stress in the patient's life and replace them with more realistic ones.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Once the negative schemas have been replaced, this will hopefully lead to remission of the patient's symptoms.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] CBT is considered particularly effective in the treatment of depression and has even been used in recent years in group settings.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] It is felt that using CBT in a group setting aids in giving its members a sense of support and decreasing the likelihood of them dropping out of therapy before the treatment has had time to work properly.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] CBT is an effective treatment for many patients, even those who do not have diseases and disorders typically thought of as psychiatric ones.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] For example, patients with the disease multiple sclerosis have found a lot of help using CBT.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] The treatment often helps the patients cope with the disorder they have and how they can adapt to their new lives without developing new problems, such as depression or negative schemas about themselves.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] According to RAND, therapies are difficult to provide to all patients in need.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] A lack of funding and understanding of symptoms provides a major roadblock that is not easily avoided.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Individual symptoms and responses to treatment vary, creating a disconnect among patients, society, and caregivers/professionals.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] In play therapy, the clinicians will "play" with their client, usually with toys or a tea party.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Playing is typical child behavior; therefore, playing with the therapist will come naturally to the child.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] While playing together, the clinician will ask the patient questions, and in this setting, they seem less intrusive, more therapeutic, and more like a normal conversation.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] This should help the patient identify their issues and disclose them to the therapist with less difficulty than they may experience in a traditional counseling setting.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Play therapy involves a therapist observing a child as the child plays with toys and interacts with their surrounding environment.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] The therapist plays both an observational and an interactional role in the intervention.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] This process allows the child to enact their problems through play and speak more comfortably with the therapist.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Although somewhat controversial, due to data that suggests a lack of effectiveness in children older than 10 years old, play therapy is a valuable treatment.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] This therapy is particularly useful for younger children under 10 who are consciously aware of their environment.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Play therapy is important, given that many therapeutic interventions effective for adults are less effective for children.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Family systems therapies are based on the belief that children's problems stem from issues within the family.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Family systems therapy aims to improve relationships among multiple people within specific families through therapeutic intervention.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] For the best effect, it is recommended that the entire family be included in the therapy.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] The treatments include family management skill development and child–parent attachment development.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] These interventions help to improve family functioning.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Family therapists can teach family management skills, including improving supervision and disciplinary practices and creating environments that foster positive interactions between parents and children.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Child–parent attachment development involves altering or creating relationships between parents and children, in attempts to create secure bases for the child, and to facilitate trust, independence, and positive perceptions of family relationships.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] We see these situations a lot more than we think, which makes some spectrums of abnormal psychology more normal and more common.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] These goals are often achieved by creating understanding regarding behaviors, creating opportunities for attachment, and increasing the family's ability to think about their history and relationships.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] One of the primary criticisms of the term "Abnormal Psychology" is its contribution to the stigmatization of individuals with mental health conditions.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] The label "abnormal" implies a deviation from a societal norm, which can reinforce negative stereotypes and social exclusion.
[src:archaeology/abnormal-psychology] Critics argue that such language can lead to individuals feeling marginalized, perpetuating a sense of "otherness" and reinforcing the stigma associated with mental health issues.
[src:archaeology/about-com] In August 2012, About.com became a property of IAC, owner of Ask.com and numerous other online brands.
[src:archaeology/about-com] Its revenue is generated by advertising.
[src:archaeology/about-com] Dotdash Meredith was headquartered in New York City and maintained offices elsewhere in the New York metropolitan area, in Des Moines, Iowa, and in Birmingham, Alabama.
[src:archaeology/about-com] The Dotdash Meredith name was acquired in 2021 after IAC acquired Meredith Corporation, which had itself acquired and absorbed Time Inc.
[src:archaeology/about-com] Time had merged with Warner Communications in 1990 to form Time Warner (TW), but was spun off as a publicly traded company in 2014.
[src:archaeology/about-com] TW kept its legal name until being acquired by AT&T in 2018 and being renamed WarnerMedia (and then Warner Bros.
[src:archaeology/about-com] Founded in 1996 as The Mining Company, the site was launched on April 21, 1997 by Scott Kurnit, owner of General Internet, Bill Day, and a group of other entrepreneurs in New York City.
[src:archaeology/about-com] The original goal was to maintain 1,800 topic areas, but after five years of operation, this number was reduced to around 700.
[src:archaeology/about-com] In May 1999, the company changed its name to "About Inc." and the website name from "miningco.com" to "about.com".
[src:archaeology/about-com] The company was acquired by Primedia (now Rent Group), in 2000 through a deal valued at US$690 million, whereby Primedia swapped 45.2 million shares for About, Inc.'s 18.1 million shares.
[src:archaeology/about-com] Following the purchase, which was finalized in the first quarter of 2001, the combined company was called "Primedia" and Kurnit remained chief executive officer (CEO).
[src:archaeology/about-com] In February 2005, The New York Times Company (Times Co.) announced it was buying About.com, a purchase that was completed in the first half of the year for US$410 million.
[src:archaeology/about-com] Google and Yahoo! were reportedly among the other bidders.
[src:archaeology/about-com] Following the Times Co. acquisition, Peter C.
[src:archaeology/about-com] Horan was appointed as About Inc.'s president and CEO, but he was soon replaced by Scott Meyer in May 2005.
[src:archaeology/about-com] In March 2007, About.com's patronage was measured at 33.5 million unique visitors.
[src:archaeology/about-com] On May 7, 2007, About Inc. acquired ConsumerSearch.com—a site that generated 3 million unique monthly visitors during the first quarter of 2007—for US $33 million in cash following two other purchases that were made in the preceding eight-month period: UCompareHealthCare.com and Calorie-Count.com.
[src:archaeology/about-com] Initially conceived in January 2007, About.com's first fully owned foreign venture, the China-based Abang.com, debuted in December 2007.
[src:archaeology/about-com] At the time of the launch, the company had a Japan-based online entity, Allabout.co.jp, but it functioned under a licensing agreement.
[src:archaeology/about-com] By January 2008, the China site consisted of around 25 employees, as well as 80 guides who were responsible for article production within seven categories: Fashion, Food, Health, Hobbies, Pets, Digital, and Travel.
[src:archaeology/about-com] As part of the localization process, the China initiative—led by Matt Roberts, who became the CEO of Abang.com, and Wen-Wei Wang, the vice president of technology for the launch—was named "Abang" because the Chinese character "bang" refers to the concept of a group or community.
[src:archaeology/about-com] The About Group generated US $102.7 million in 2007, which represented a 135% increase from the time of the Times Co. acquisition.
[src:archaeology/about-com] Meyer stepped down from the chief executive role in March 2008 and was replaced by Cella Irvine, who previously worked for Hearst Corp. and Microsoft Corp.
[src:archaeology/about-com] In April 2011, Irvine launched the About en Español website, which was About's first Spanish-language channel and initially featured nine topics, including movies and makeup, that were to be expanded by around 100 by the start of 2012.
[src:archaeology/about-com] The launch was part of an overall strategy that included a redesigned About.com homepage, a doubling of the number of "how-to" and do-it-yourself videos on About.com's 24 channels, and new outlets on About.com for advertisers.
[src:archaeology/about-com] The significant impact of the Great Recession upon online advertising was experienced shortly after Irvine's appointment, and she was removed from the CEO role after three years and three consecutive quarters in which revenue decreased.
[src:archaeology/about-com] Martin Nisenholtz, SVP of digital operations, temporarily replaced Irvine following her departure in May 2011.
[src:archaeology/about-com] In July 2011, Darline Jean was named CEO of the About Group, after the company's second-quarter revenues were $27.8 million.
[src:archaeology/about-com] Jean had been its chief financial officer (CFO) and was promoted in September 2011.
[src:archaeology/about-com] A media report published in August 2012 indicated that Answers.com had reached a preliminary agreement to acquire About.com for US$270 million.
[src:archaeology/about-com] However, on August 26, Barry Diller's IAC announced that it would acquire About.com instead for US$300 million in cash.
[src:archaeology/about-com] A source for TechCrunch later confirmed that Answers.com's offer was reportedly valued at US$270 million, but consisted of debt and equity in Answers.com.
[src:archaeology/about-com] In the corresponding press release, IAC explained that the acquisition would help bolster and accompany its existing properties, such as the Ask.com web search engine.
[src:archaeology/about-com] Jean fulfilled her role as chief executive during the transition period, while ownership was transferred to IAC, and then left About.com shortly after the sale was finalized.
[src:archaeology/about-com] At the time of the IAC acquisition, which was signed on August 26, 2012, About.com consisted of nearly 1,000 topic sites and over three million unique articles, while, in traffic terms, Alexa Internet ranked the site as number 37 in the U.S. and 80 in the global context.
[src:archaeology/about-com] On April 2, 2013, Neil Vogel became the new CEO of About.com.
[src:archaeology/about-com] Up until March 2003, Vogel was a key executive member of the marketing and media company Alloy Inc., a role that he left to cofound the Recognition Media marketing business that is responsible for producing the annual Webby Awards event, as well as the Internet Week NY and Europe events.
[src:archaeology/about-com] Vogel was selected by *Business Insider* for its 2012 "The Coolest People In New York Tech This Year" list, for his work as a venture partner of FirstMark Capital.
[src:archaeology/about-com] As of May 2013, About.com was receiving about 84 million unique monthly visitors.
[src:archaeology/about-com] Following his appointment, Vogel's overall plan for About focused on social, mobile, and user experience, with an emphasis on increasing the amount of time that users remain on the site, rather than attracting people in the first instance.
[src:archaeology/about-com] Vogel further explained that IAC has been able to create "compelling" content that manages to successfully engage Internet users, while About's content, in particular, is favored by the Google search engine.
[src:archaeology/about-com] In April 2014, Vogel revealed to the media that the About.com team had grown from 100 employees to 176, and the number of site contributors had increased by 20 percent.
[src:archaeology/about-com] The company's developers updated the website's backend to be capable of handling a greater degree of interactivity at the front end, while a major emphasis was placed on responsive web design, as the traffic from mobile devices and tablets was measured at nearly 40 percent.
[src:archaeology/about-com] The About.com website was relaunched in September 2014, following a significant redesign that expanded upon the new homepage that debuted in July 2014.
[src:archaeology/about-com] Based on an analysis of the needs of both users and advertisers, the redesign sought to create an improved user experience and facilitate social sharing, including the addition of social media buttons that were not featured at the time of Vogel's appointment.
[src:archaeology/about-com] On May 2, 2017, IAC announced the completed rebranding of About.com to Dotdash, after about a year of transition.
[src:archaeology/about-com] "Dot" was a tribute to the About.com logo, and "Dash" signified forward motion.
[src:archaeology/about-com] CEO Neil Vogel said that the company had lost mind share and needed to change its marketing strategy.
[src:archaeology/about-com] According to *WIRED*, the About.com brand was retired, despite its profitability, to make way for a new business model.
[src:archaeology/about-com] The company refocused on vertical markets through its niche websites: *The Balance* (personal finance), *Lifewire* (tech), *The Spruce* (home and food), *VeryWell* (health), *TripSavvy* (travel), and *ThoughtCo* (education).
[src:archaeology/about-com] On March 29, 2018, Dotdash won Digiday's Publisher of the Year.
[src:archaeology/about-com] In July 2018, Dotdash acquired *Investopedia*.
[src:archaeology/about-com] On October 15, TripSavvy launched the Editors' Choice Awards.
[src:archaeology/about-com] On January 8, 2019, Dotdash announced the acquisition of *Byrdie* (beauty) and *MyDomaine* (women's lifestyle) from Clique Brands.
[src:archaeology/about-com] On May 15, Dotdash announced the acquisition of *Brides* from Conde Nast.
[src:archaeology/about-com] In the spring of 2019, Dotdash's home site, *The Spruce*, announced the launch of its first-ever paint collection, The Spruce Best Home, in partnership with KILZ and sold exclusively on Amazon.
[src:archaeology/about-com] On October 1, Dotdash announced the acquisition of Liquor.com.
[src:archaeology/about-com] On February 4, 2020, Dotdash announced the acquisition of *TreeHugger* and Mother Nature Network.
[src:archaeology/about-com] In June, Dotdash was named Digiday's Publisher of the Year in Digiday's Media Awards 2020.
[src:archaeology/about-com] *The Spruce* won for Best User Experience and CEO Neil Vogel won Executive of the Year.
[src:archaeology/about-com] On September 22, Dotdash announced that it acquired *Simply Recipes* and *Serious Eats* from Fexy Media.
[src:archaeology/about-com] On October 6, 2021, Dotdash announced the acquisition of Meredith's magazine and other non-broadcast assets (including the former Time Inc. assets) for $2.7 billion, forming a new entity called Dotdash Meredith.
[src:archaeology/about-com] The transaction was finalized on December 1.
[src:archaeology/about-com] On February 9, 2022, Dotdash CEO Neil Vogel issued a memo revealing that six former Meredith Corporation magazines (*Entertainment Weekly*, *InStyle*, *EatingWell*, *Health*, *Parents*, and *People en Español*) would cease print circulation and switch to a digital-only format.
[src:archaeology/about-com] On July 31, 2025, the company announced it had rebranded as People Inc.
[src:archaeology/about-com] Its offer would value the company at $12.4 billion.
[src:archaeology/about-com] People Inc. has offices at three locations in the USA including New York, Des Moines, and Birmingham.
[src:archaeology/academic-discipline] An **academic discipline** or **academic field** is a subdivision of knowledge that is taught and researched at the college or university level.
[src:archaeology/academic-discipline] Disciplines are defined (in part) and recognized by the academic journals in which research is published, and the learned societies and academic departments or faculties within colleges and universities to which their practitioners belong.
[src:archaeology/academic-discipline] Academic disciplines are conventionally divided into the humanities (including philosophy, languages, art and cultural studies), the natural sciences (such as physics, chemistry, and biology); and the formal sciences like mathematics and computer science.
[src:archaeology/academic-discipline] The social sciences are sometimes considered a fourth category.
[src:archaeology/academic-discipline] It is also known as a *field of study*, *field of inquiry*, *research field* and *branch of knowledge*.
[src:archaeology/academic-discipline] The different terms are used in different countries and fields.
[src:archaeology/academic-discipline] Individuals associated with academic disciplines are commonly referred to as *experts* or *specialists*.
[src:archaeology/academic-discipline] Others, who may have studied liberal arts or systems theory rather than concentrating in a specific academic discipline, are classified as *generalists*.
[src:archaeology/academic-discipline] For example, professionals may encounter trouble communicating across academic disciplines because of differences in jargon, concepts, or methodology.
[src:archaeology/academic-discipline] Some researchers believe that academic disciplines may, in the future, be replaced by what is known as Mode 2 or "post-academic science", which involves the acquisition of cross-disciplinary knowledge through the collaboration of specialists from various academic disciplines.
[src:archaeology/academic-discipline] The University of Paris in 1231 consisted of four faculties:- Theology, Medicine, Canon Law and Arts.
[src:archaeology/academic-discipline] Educational institutions originally used the term "discipline" to catalog and archive the new and expanding body of information produced by the scholarly community.
[src:archaeology/academic-discipline] Disciplinary designations originated in German universities during the beginning of the nineteenth century.
[src:archaeology/academic-discipline] In the early twentieth century, new academic disciplines such as education and psychology were added.
[src:archaeology/academic-discipline] In the 1970s and 1980s, there was an explosion of new academic disciplines focusing on specific themes, such as media studies, women's studies, and Africana studies.
[src:archaeology/academic-discipline] Many academic disciplines designed as preparation for careers and professions, such as nursing, hospitality management, and corrections, also emerged in the universities.
[src:archaeology/academic-discipline] Finally, interdisciplinary scientific fields of study such as biochemistry and geophysics gained prominence as their contribution to knowledge became widely recognized.
[src:archaeology/academic-discipline] Some new disciplines, such as public administration, can be found in more than one disciplinary setting; some public administration programs are associated with business schools (thus emphasizing management), while others are linked to political science (emphasizing policy analysis).
[src:archaeology/academic-discipline] As the twentieth century approached, these designations were gradually adopted by other countries and became the accepted conventional subjects.
[src:archaeology/academic-discipline] However, these designations differed between various countries.
[src:archaeology/academic-discipline] In the twentieth century, the natural science disciplines included: physics, chemistry, biology, geology, and astronomy.
[src:archaeology/academic-discipline] The social science disciplines included: economics, politics, sociology, and psychology.
[src:archaeology/academic-discipline] Prior to the twentieth century, categories were broad and general, which was expected due to the lack of interest in science at the time.
[src:archaeology/academic-discipline] Most practitioners of science were amateurs and were referred to as "natural historians" and "natural philosophers"—labels that date back to Aristotle—instead of "scientists".
[src:archaeology/academic-discipline] Natural history referred to what we now call life sciences and natural philosophy referred to the current physical sciences.
[src:archaeology/academic-discipline] Prior to the twentieth century, few opportunities existed for science as an occupation outside the educational system.
[src:archaeology/academic-discipline] Higher education provided the institutional structure for scientific investigation, as well as economic support for research and teaching.
[src:archaeology/academic-discipline] Soon, the volume of scientific information rapidly increased and researchers realized the importance of concentrating on smaller, narrower fields of scientific activity.
[src:archaeology/academic-discipline] Because of this narrowing, scientific specializations emerged.
[src:archaeology/academic-discipline] As these specializations developed, modern scientific disciplines in universities also improved their sophistication.
[src:archaeology/academic-discipline] Eventually, academia's identified disciplines became the foundations for scholars of specific specialized interests and expertise.
[src:archaeology/academic-discipline] An influential critique of the concept of academic disciplines came from Michel Foucault in his 1975 book, *Discipline and Punish*.
[src:archaeology/academic-discipline] Communities of academic disciplines can be found outside academia within corporations, government agencies, and independent organizations, where they take the form of associations of professionals with common interests and specific knowledge.
[src:archaeology/academic-discipline] Such communities include corporate think tanks, NASA, and IUPAC.
[src:archaeology/academic-discipline] Communities such as these exist to benefit the organizations affiliated with them by providing specialized new ideas, research, and findings.
[src:archaeology/academic-discipline] Nations at various developmental stages will find the need for different academic disciplines during different times of growth.
[src:archaeology/academic-discipline] A newly developing nation will likely prioritize government, political matters and engineering over those of the humanities, arts and social sciences.
[src:archaeology/academic-discipline] On the other hand, a well-developed nation may be capable of investing more in the arts and social sciences.
[src:archaeology/academic-discipline] Communities of academic disciplines would contribute at varying levels of importance during different stages of development.
[src:archaeology/academic-discipline] These categories explain how the different academic disciplines interact with one another.
[src:archaeology/academic-discipline] Multidisciplinary (or pluridisciplinary) knowledge is associated with more than one existing academic discipline or profession.
[src:archaeology/academic-discipline] A multidisciplinary community or project is made up of people from different academic disciplines and professions.
[src:archaeology/academic-discipline] One key question is how well the challenge can be decomposed into subparts, and then addressed via the distributed knowledge in the community.
[src:archaeology/academic-discipline] The lack of shared vocabulary between people and communication overhead can sometimes be an issue in these communities and projects.
[src:archaeology/academic-discipline] If challenges of a particular type need to be repeatedly addressed so that each one can be properly decomposed, a multidisciplinary community can be exceptionally efficient and effective.
[src:archaeology/academic-discipline] There are many examples of a particular idea appearing in different academic disciplines, all of which came about around the same time.
[src:archaeology/academic-discipline] One example of this scenario is the shift from the approach of focusing on sensory awareness of the whole, "an attention to the 'total field'", a "sense of the whole pattern, of form and function as a unity", an "integral idea of structure and configuration".
[src:archaeology/academic-discipline] This has happened in art (in the form of cubism), physics, poetry, communication and educational theory.
[src:archaeology/academic-discipline] According to Marshall McLuhan, this paradigm shift was due to the passage from the era of mechanization, which brought sequentiality, to the era of the instant speed of electricity, which brought simultaneity.
[src:archaeology/academic-discipline] Multidisciplinary approaches also encourage people to help shape the innovation of the future.
[src:archaeology/academic-discipline] The political dimensions of forming new multidisciplinary partnerships to solve the so-called societal Grand Challenges were presented in the Innovation Union and in the European Framework Programme, the Horizon 2020 operational overlay.
[src:archaeology/academic-discipline] Innovation across academic disciplines is considered the pivotal foresight of the creation of new products, systems, and processes for the benefit of all societies' growth and wellbeing.
[src:archaeology/academic-discipline] Regional examples such as Biopeople and industry-academia initiatives in translational medicine such as SHARE.ku.dk in Denmark provide evidence of the successful endeavour of multidisciplinary innovation and facilitation of the paradigm shift.
[src:archaeology/academic-discipline] In practice, transdisciplinary can be thought of as the union of all interdisciplinary efforts.
[src:archaeology/academic-discipline] While interdisciplinary teams may be creating new knowledge that lies between several existing disciplines, a transdisciplinary team is more holistic and seeks to relate all disciplines into a coherent whole.
[src:archaeology/academic-discipline] Cross-disciplinary knowledge is that which explains aspects of one discipline in terms of another.
[src:archaeology/academic-discipline] Common examples of cross-disciplinary approaches are studies of the physics of music or the politics of literature.
[src:archaeology/academic-discipline] Bibliometrics can be used to map several issues in relation to disciplines, for example, the flow of ideas within and among disciplines (Lindholm-Romantschuk, 1998) or the existence of specific national traditions within disciplines.
[src:archaeology/academic-discipline] Scholarly impact and influence of one discipline on another may be understood by analyzing the flow of citations.
[src:archaeology/academic-discipline] The Bibliometrics approach is described as straightforward because it is based on simple counting.
[src:archaeology/academic-discipline] The method is also objective but the quantitative method may not be compatible with a qualitative assessment and therefore manipulated.
[src:archaeology/academic-discipline] The number of citations is dependent on the number of persons working in the same domain instead of inherent quality or published result's originality.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Archaeologists study human prehistory and history, from the development of the first stone tools at Lomekwi in East Africa 3.3 million years ago up until recent decades.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Archaeology is distinct from palaeontology, which is the study of fossil remains.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Archaeology is particularly important for learning about prehistoric societies, for which, by definition, there are no written records.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Prehistory includes over 99% of the human past, from the Paleolithic until the advent of literacy in societies around the world.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Archaeology has various goals, ranging from understanding culture history to reconstructing past lifeways to documenting and explaining changes in human societies over time.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Derived from Greek, the term *archaeology* means "the study of ancient history".
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Archaeology developed out of antiquarianism in Europe during the 19th century and has since become a discipline practiced worldwide.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Nation-states have used archaeology to create particular visions of the past.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Since its early development, various specific sub-disciplines of archaeology have developed, including maritime archaeology, feminist archaeology, and archaeoastronomy, and numerous different scientific techniques have been developed to aid archaeological investigation.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Nonetheless, today, archaeologists face many problems, such as dealing with pseudoarchaeology, the looting of artifacts, a lack of public interest, and opposition to the excavation of human remains.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] In Ancient Mesopotamia, a foundation deposit of the Akkadian Empire ruler Naram-Sin (ruled c.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] 2200 BC) was discovered and analysed by king Nabonidus, c.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] 550 BC, who is thus known as the first archaeologist.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] He was also the first to date an archaeological artifact in his attempt to date Naram-Sin's temple during his search for it.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Even though his estimate was inaccurate by about 1,500 years, it was still a very good one considering the lack of accurate dating technology at the time.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] The science of archaeology (from Greek ἀρχαιολογία *archaiologia*, from ἀρχαῖος, *arkhaios* 'ancient' and -λογία, *-logia* 'study') grew out of the older multi-disciplinary study known as antiquarianism.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Antiquarians studied history with particular attention to ancient artifacts, manuscripts, and historical sites.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Antiquarianism focused on the empirical evidence available for understanding the past, encapsulated in the motto of the 18th century antiquary Richard Colt Hoare: "We speak from facts, not theory".
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Tentative steps towards the systematization of archaeology as a science took place during the Enlightenment period in Europe in the 17th and 18th centuries.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] In Imperial China during the Song dynasty (960–1279), figures such as Ouyang Xiu and Zhao Mingcheng established the tradition of Chinese epigraphy by investigating, preserving, and analyzing ancient Chinese bronze inscriptions from the Shang and Zhou periods.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Such antiquarian pursuits waned after the Song period, were revived in the 17th century during the Qing dynasty, but were always considered a branch of Chinese historiography rather than a separate discipline of archaeology.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] In Renaissance Europe, philosophical interest in the remains of Greco-Roman civilization and the rediscovery of classical culture began in the late Middle Ages, with humanism.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Cyriacus of Ancona was a restlessly itinerant Italian humanist and antiquarian who came from a prominent family of merchants in Ancona, a maritime republic on the Adriatic.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] He noted down his archaeological discoveries in his diary, *Commentaria* (in six volumes).
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Flavio Biondo, an Italian Renaissance humanist historian, created a systematic guide to the ruins and topography of ancient Rome in the early 15th century, for which he has been called an early founder of archaeology.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Antiquarians of the 16th century, including John Leland and William Camden, conducted surveys of the English countryside, drawing, describing and interpreting the monuments that they encountered.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] The *Oxford English Dictionary* first cites "archaeologist" in 1824; this soon became the usual term for one major branch of antiquarian activity.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] "Archaeology", from 1607 onward, initially meant what we would call "ancient history" generally, with the narrower modern sense first seen in 1837.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Twelfth-century Indian scholar Kalhana's writings involved recording local traditions and examining manuscripts, inscriptions, coins, and architecture, which are described as among the earliest traces of archaeology.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] One of his notable works is called *Rajatarangini*, which was completed c.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] 1150 and is considered one of the first historical works of India.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Among the first sites to undergo archaeological excavation were Stonehenge and other megalithic monuments in England.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] John Aubrey (1626–1697) was a pioneer archaeologist who recorded numerous megalithic and other field monuments in southern England.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] He was also ahead of his time in analysing his findings.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] He attempted to chart the chronological stylistic evolution of handwriting, medieval architecture, costume, and shield-shapes.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Excavations were also carried out by the Spanish military engineer Roque Joaquín de Alcubierre in the ancient towns of Pompeii and Herculaneum, both of which had been covered by ash during the Eruption of Mount Vesuvius in AD 79.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] These excavations began in 1748 in Pompeii and in 1738 in Herculaneum.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] The discovery of entire towns, complete with utensils and even human shapes, as well as the unearthing of frescos, had a big impact throughout Europe.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] However, before the development of modern techniques, excavations tended to be haphazard; the importance of concepts such as stratification and context was overlooked.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] In the mid-18th century, the German Johann Joachim Winckelmann lived in Rome and devoted himself to the study of Roman antiquities, gradually acquiring an unrivalled knowledge of ancient art.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Then, he visited the archaeological excavations being conducted at Pompeii and Herculaneum.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] He was one of the founders of scientific archaeology and first applied the categories of style on a large, systematic basis to the history of art.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] He was one of the first to separate Greek art into periods and time classifications.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Winckelmann has been called both "The prophet and founding hero of modern archaeology" and the father of the discipline of art history.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] The father of archaeological excavation was William Cunnington (1754–1810).
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] He undertook excavations in Wiltshire from around 1798, funded by Sir Richard Colt Hoare.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Cunnington made meticulous recordings of Neolithic and Bronze Age barrows, and the terms he used to categorize and describe them are still used by archaeologists today.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] President Thomas Jefferson also did his own excavations in 1784 using the trench method, on several Native American burial mounds in Virginia.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] His excavations were prompted by the "Moundbuilders" question; however, his careful methods led him to conclude that there was no reason why the ancestors of the Native Americans of his time could not have raised those mounds.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] One of the major achievements of 19th-century archaeology was the development of stratigraphy.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] The idea of overlapping strata tracing back to successive periods was borrowed from the new geological and palaeontological work of scholars like William Smith, James Hutton, and Charles Lyell.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] The systematic application of stratigraphy to archaeology first occurred during excavations of prehistorical and Bronze Age sites.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] In the third and fourth decades of the 19th century, archaeologists such as Jacques Boucher de Perthes and Christian Jürgensen Thomsen began to arrange the artifacts they had found in chronological order.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] A major figure in the development of archaeology into a rigorous science was army officer and ethnologist Augustus Pitt Rivers, who began excavations on his land in England in the 1880s.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Highly methodical by the standards of the time, he is widely regarded as the first scientific archaeologist.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] He arranged his artifacts by type or "Typology (archaeology)", and within types chronologically.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] This style of arrangement, designed to highlight evolutionary trends in human artifacts, was of enormous significance for accurately dating the objects.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] His most important methodological innovation was his insistence that *all* artifacts, not just beautiful or unique ones, be collected and catalogued.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] William Flinders Petrie is another man who may legitimately be called the Father of Archaeology.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Petrie was the first to scientifically investigate the Great Pyramid in Egypt during the 1880s.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] He was also responsible for mentoring and training a whole generation of Egyptologists, including Howard Carter who went on to achieve fame with the discovery of the tomb of 14th-century BC pharaoh Tutankhamun.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] The first stratigraphic excavation to gain wide public popularity was that of Hissarlik, on the site of ancient Troy, carried out by Heinrich Schliemann, Frank Calvert, and Wilhelm Dörpfeld in the 1870s.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] These scholars individuated nine different cities that had overlapped with one another, from prehistory to the Hellenistic period.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Meanwhile, the work of Sir Arthur Evans at Knossos in Crete revealed the ancient existence of an equally advanced Minoan civilization.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] The next major figure in the development of archaeology was Sir Mortimer Wheeler, whose highly disciplined approach to excavation and systematic coverage in the 1920s and 1930s brought the science on swiftly.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Wheeler developed the grid system of excavation, which was further improved by his student Kathleen Kenyon.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Archaeology became a professional activity in the first half of the 20th century, and it became possible to study archaeology as a subject in universities and even schools.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] By the end of the 20th century, nearly all professional archaeologists, at least in developed countries, were graduates.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Further adaptation and innovation in archaeology continued in this period, when maritime archaeology and urban archaeology became more prevalent, and rescue archaeology was developed in response to increasing commercial development.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] The purpose of archaeology is to learn more about past societies and the development of the human race.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Over 99% of human development has occurred within prehistoric cultures, which did not use writing; no written records exist for study.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Without such written sources, the only way to understand prehistoric societies is through archaeology.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Because archaeology is the study of past human activity, it stretches back to about 2.5 million years ago when the first stone tools were found – The Oldowan Industry.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Many important developments in human history occurred during prehistory, such as the evolution of humanity during the Paleolithic period, when the hominins developed from the australopithecines in Africa and eventually into modern *Homo sapiens*.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Archaeology also sheds light on many of humanity's technological advances, for instance, the ability to use fire, the development of stone tools, the discovery of metallurgy, the beginnings of religion, and the creation of agriculture.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Without archaeology, little or nothing would be known about humanity's use of material culture that predates writing.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] However, it is not only prehistoric, pre-literate cultures that can be studied using archaeology; historic, literate cultures can also be studied through the sub-discipline of historical archaeology.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] For many literate cultures, such as Ancient Greece and Mesopotamia, their surviving records are often incomplete and biased to some extent.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] In many societies, literacy was restricted to the elite classes, such as the clergy or the bureaucracy of the court or the temple.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] The literacy of aristocrats has sometimes been restricted to deeds and contracts.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] The interests and worldview of elites are often quite different from those of the populace.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Writings that were produced by people more representative of the general population were unlikely to find their way into libraries and be preserved there for posterity.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Thus, written records tend to reflect the biases, assumptions, cultural values, and possibly deceptions of a limited range of individuals, usually a small fraction of the larger population.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Hence, written records cannot be trusted as a sole source.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] The material record may be closer to a fair representation of society, though it is subject to its own biases, such as sampling bias and differential preservation.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Often, archaeology provides the only means of learning about the existence and behavior of people in the past.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Over the millennia, many thousands of cultures and societies, and billions of people, have come and gone, with little or no written record, or with existing records that are misrepresentative or incomplete.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Writing, as it is known today, did not exist in human civilization until the 4th millennium BC, and even then, only in a relatively small number of technologically advanced civilizations.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] In contrast, *Homo sapiens* has existed for at least 200,000 years, and other *Homo* species for millions of years (see Human evolution).
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] These civilizations are, not coincidentally, the best known; they have been open to historical inquiry for centuries, whereas the study of prehistoric cultures has only recently emerged.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Within a literate civilization, many events and important human practices may not be officially recorded.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Any knowledge of the early years of human civilization – the development of agriculture, cult practices of folk religion, the rise of the first cities – must come from archaeology.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] In addition to their scientific importance, archaeological remains sometimes have political or cultural significance for the descendants of the people who produced them, monetary value for collectors, or strong aesthetic appeal.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Many people identify archaeology with the recovery of such aesthetic, religious, political, or economic treasures rather than with the reconstruction of past societies.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] This view is often espoused in works of popular fiction, such as Raiders of the Lost Ark, The Mummy, and King Solomon's Mines.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] When unrealistic subjects are treated more seriously, accusations of pseudoscience are invariably levelled at their proponents *(see Pseudoarchaeology)*.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] However, these endeavours, real and fictional, are not representative of modern archaeology.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] There is no single approach to archaeological theory adopted by all archaeologists.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] In the 1960s, an archaeological movement largely led by American archaeologists like Lewis Binford and Kent Flannery arose that rebelled against the established cultural-history archaeology.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] They proposed a "New Archaeology", which would be more "scientific" and "anthropological", with hypothesis testing and the scientific method very important parts of what became known as processual archaeology.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] In the 1980s, a new postmodern movement arose led by the British archaeologists Michael Shanks, Christopher Tilley, Daniel Miller, and Ian Hodder, which has become known as post-processual archaeology.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] It questioned processualism's appeals to scientific positivism and impartiality; it emphasized the importance of a more self-critical theoretical reflexivity.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] However, processualists have criticized this approach as lacking scientific rigour.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] The validity of both processualism and post-processualism is still under debate.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Meanwhile, another theory, known as historical processualism, has emerged seeking to incorporate a focus on process and post-processual archaeology's emphasis on reflexivity and history.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] An archaeological investigation usually involves several distinct phases, each employing a variety of methods.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Before any practical work can begin, however, a clear objective for what the archaeologists are seeking to achieve must be agreed upon.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] This done, a site is surveyed to learn as much as possible about it and its surroundings.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Second, an excavation may be conducted to uncover any buried archaeological features.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] And third, the information collected during the excavation is studied and evaluated to achieve the archaeologists' original research objectives.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] It is then considered good practice for the information to be published so that it is available to other archaeologists and historians, although this is sometimes neglected.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Before actually starting to dig at a location, remote sensing can be used to identify where sites are located within a large area or to provide more information about sites or regions.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] There are two types of remote sensing instruments—passive and active.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Passive instruments detect natural energy reflected or emitted by the observed scene.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Passive instruments sense only radiation emitted by the object being viewed or reflected by the object from a source other than the instrument.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Active instruments emit energy and record the reflections.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Satellite imagery is an example of passive remote sensing.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] The distance to the object is determined by recording the time between the transmitted and backscattered pulses and using the speed of light to calculate the distance travelled.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Lidars can determine atmospheric profiles of aerosols, clouds, and other atmospheric constituents.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] The archaeological project then continues (or begins) with a field survey.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] A regional survey is an attempt to locate previously unknown sites within a region systematically.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] A site survey is an attempt to systematically locate features of interest, such as houses and middens, within a site.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Each of these two goals may be accomplished with largely the same methods.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Surveys were not widely practised in the early days of archaeology.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Cultural historians and earlier researchers were usually content to discover the locations of monumental sites from the local populace and to excavate only the plainly visible features there.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Gordon Willey pioneered the technique of regional settlement pattern survey in 1949 in the Viru Valley of coastal Peru, and survey of all levels became prominent with the rise of processual archaeology some years later.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Survey work has many benefits if performed as a preliminary exercise to, or even in place of, excavation.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] It requires relatively little time and expense because it does not involve processing large volumes of soil to search for artifacts.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] (Nevertheless, surveying a large region or site can be expensive, so archaeologists often employ sampling methods.) As with other forms of non-destructive archaeology, survey avoids ethical issues (of particular concern to descendant peoples) associated with destroying a site through excavation.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] It is the only way to gather some forms of information, such as settlement patterns and settlement structure.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Survey data are commonly assembled into maps, which may show surface features and/or artifact distribution.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] The simplest survey technique is a surface survey.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] It involves combing an area, usually on foot but sometimes using mechanized transport, to search for features or artifacts visible on the surface.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Surface survey cannot detect sites or features that are completely buried under earth or overgrown with vegetation.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Surface survey may also include mini-excavation techniques such as augers, corers, and shovel test pits.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] If no materials are found, the area surveyed is deemed sterile.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Aerial survey is conducted using cameras attached to airplanes, balloons, UAVs, or even Kites.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] A bird's-eye view is useful for quick mapping of large or complex sites.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Aerial photographs are used to document the status of the archaeological dig.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Aerial imaging can also detect many things not visible from the surface.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Plants growing above a buried human-made structure, such as a stone wall, will develop more slowly, while those above other types of features (such as middens) may develop more rapidly.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Photographs of ripening grain, which changes colour rapidly at maturation, have revealed buried structures with great precision.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Aerial photographs taken at different times of day will help show the outlines of structures by changes in shadows.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Aerial survey also employs ultraviolet, infrared, ground-penetrating radar wavelengths, Lidar and thermography.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Geophysical survey can be the most effective way to see beneath the ground.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Magnetometers detect minute deviations in the Earth's magnetic field caused by iron artifacts, kilns, some types of stone structures, and even ditches and middens.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Devices that measure the electrical resistivity of the soil are also widely used.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Archaeological features whose electrical resistivity contrasts with that of surrounding soils can be detected and mapped.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Some archaeological features (such as those composed of stone or brick) have higher resistivity than typical soils.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] In comparison, others (such as organic deposits or unfired clay) tend to have lower resistivity.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Although some archaeologists consider the use of metal detectors to be tantamount to treasure hunting, others deem them an effective tool in archaeological surveying.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Examples of formal archaeological use of metal detectors include musketball distribution analysis on English Civil War battlefields, metal distribution analysis before excavation of a 19th-century ship wreck, and service cable location during evaluation.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Metal detectorists have also contributed to archaeology, where they have made detailed records of their results and refrained from raising artifacts from their archaeological context.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] In the UK, metal detectorists have been invited to participate in the Portable Antiquities Scheme.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Regional survey in underwater archaeology uses geophysical or remote sensing devices such as a marine magnetometer, side-scan sonar, or sub-bottom sonar.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Archaeological excavation has existed even when the field was still the domain of amateurs, and it remains the primary source of data recovered in most field projects.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] It can reveal several types of information that are usually not accessible through surveys, such as stratigraphy, three-dimensional structure, and verifiably primary context.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Modern excavation techniques require that the precise locations of objects and features, known as their provenance or provenience, be recorded.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] This always involves determining their horizontal locations and, sometimes, their vertical positions as well (see also Primary Laws of Archaeology).
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Likewise, their association, or relationship with nearby objects and features, needs to be recorded for later analysis.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] This allows the archaeologist to deduce which artifacts and features were likely used together and which may be from different phases of activity.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] For example, excavation of a site reveals its stratigraphy; if a succession of distinct cultures occupied a site, artifacts from more recent cultures will lie above those from earlier ones.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Excavation is the most expensive phase of archaeological research, in relative terms.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Also, as a destructive process, it carries ethical concerns.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] As a result, very few sites are excavated in their entirety.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Again, the percentage of a site excavated depends greatly on the country and the "method statement" issued.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Sampling is even more important in excavation than in survey.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Sometimes large mechanical equipment, such as backhoes (JCBs), is used in excavation, especially to remove the topsoil (overburden), though this method is increasingly used with great caution.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Following this rather dramatic step, the exposed area is usually hand-cleaned with trowels or hoes to ensure that all features are apparent.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] The next task is to create a site plan and then use it to help determine the excavation method.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Features dug into the natural subsoil are normally excavated in portions to produce a visible archaeological section for recording.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] A feature, for example, a pit or a ditch, consists of two parts: the cut and the fill.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] The cut describes the edge of the feature where it meets the natural soil.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] The fill is what the feature is filled with, and will often appear quite distinct from the natural soil.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] The cut and fill are given consecutive numbers for recording purposes.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Scaled plans and sections of individual features are all drawn on site; black-and-white and colour photographs of them are taken; and recording sheets are filled in, describing the context of each feature.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] All this information serves as a permanent record of the now-destroyed archaeology and is used to describe and interpret the site.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Once artifacts and structures have been excavated or collected during surface surveys, they must be studied properly.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] This process is known as post-excavation analysis, and is usually the most time-consuming part of an archaeological investigation.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] It is not uncommon for final excavation reports for major sites to take years to be published.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] At a basic level of analysis, artifacts found are cleaned, catalogued and compared to published collections.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] This comparison process often involves classifying them typologically and identifying other sites with similar artifact assemblages.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] However, a much broader range of analytical techniques is available through archaeological science, allowing artifacts to be dated and their compositions examined.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Bones, plants, and pollen collected from a site can all be analysing using the methods of zooarchaeology, paleoethnobotany, palynology and stable isotopes while any texts can usually be deciphered.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] These techniques frequently provide information that would not otherwise be known, thereby contributing greatly to understanding a site.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] As with most academic disciplines, there are a very large number of archaeological sub-disciplines characterized by a specific method or type of material (e.g., lithic analysis, music, archaeobotany), geographical or chronological focus (e.g.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Near Eastern archaeology, Islamic archaeology, Medieval archaeology), other thematic concern (e.g. maritime archaeology, landscape archaeology, battlefield archaeology), or a specific archaeological culture or civilization (e.g.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Historical archaeology is the study of cultures with some form of writing and deals with objects and issues from the past.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] In medieval Europe, archaeologists have explored the illicit burial of unbaptized children in medieval texts and cemeteries.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] In downtown New York City, archaeologists have exhumed the 18th century remains of the African Burial Ground.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] When remnants of the WWII Siegfried Line were being destroyed, emergency archaeological digs were conducted whenever any part of the line was removed, to advance scientific knowledge and reveal details of its construction.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Ethnoarchaeology is the ethnographic study of living people, designed to aid in our interpretation of the archaeological record.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] The approach first gained prominence during the processual movement of the 1960s, and continues to be a vibrant component of post-processual and other current archaeological approaches.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Early ethnoarchaeological research focused on hunter-gatherer or foraging societies; today, ethnoarchaeological research encompasses a much wider range of human behaviour.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Experimental archaeology represents the application of the experimental method to develop more highly controlled observations of processes that create and impact the archaeological record.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] In the context of the logical positivism of processualism with its goals of improving the scientific rigor of archaeological epistemologies, the experimental method gained importance.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Experimental techniques remain a crucial component to improving the inferential frameworks for interpreting the archaeological record.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Archaeometry aims to systematize archaeological measurement.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] It emphasizes the application of analytical techniques from physics, chemistry, and engineering.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] It is a field of research that frequently focuses on determining the chemical composition of archaeological remains for source analysis.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Archaeometry also investigates different spatial characteristics of features, employing methods such as space syntax techniques and geodesy as well as computer-based tools such as geographic information system technology.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Rare earth elements patterns may also be used.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] A relatively nascent subfield is that of archaeological materials, designed to enhance understanding of prehistoric and non-industrial culture through scientific analysis of the structure and properties of materials associated with human activity.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Digital Archeology is an interdisciplinary field that applies information technology (IT), digital tools, and data management techniques to archaeology.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] It includes virtual archeology and computational archeology.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Examples of digital archaeology include the use of computer graphics to create virtual 3D models of sites, like the throne room of an Assyrian palace or ancient Rome.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Photogrammetry and digital topographical models are combined with astronomical calculations to check if structures, such as pillars, align with astronomical events like the sun's position at a solstice.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Agent-based modelling and simulation are used to understand past social dynamics and outcomes.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Data mining is applied to large collections of archaeological 'grey literature'.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Archaeology can be a subsidiary activity within Cultural resource management (CRM), also called Cultural heritage management (CHM) in the UK.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] CRM archaeologists frequently examine archaeological sites threatened by development.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] CRM accounts for most archaeological research done in the US and much of that in western Europe.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] In the US, CRM archaeology has been a growing concern since the passage of the National Historic Preservation Act (NHPA) of 1966.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Most scholars and politicians believe CRM has helped preserve much of the US's history and prehistory that would otherwise have been lost to the expansion of cities, dams, and highways.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Along with other statutes, the NHPA mandates that projects on federal land, or involving federal funds or permits, consider the effects of the project on each archaeological site.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] The application of CRM in the UK is not limited to government-funded projects.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Since 1990, PPG 16 has required planners to consider archaeology as a material consideration in determining applications for new development.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] As a result, archaeological organizations undertake mitigation work in advance of or during construction in archaeologically sensitive areas, at the developer's expense.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Some of the largest archaeological projects ever undertaken in the UK are due to major infrastructure projects such as the A14 road improvement scheme and the construction of HS2.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] In England, ultimate responsibility of care for the historic environment rests with the Department for Culture, Media and Sport in association with English Heritage.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] In Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland, the same responsibilities lie with Historic Scotland, Cadw and the Northern Ireland Environment Agency respectively.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] In France, the Institut national du patrimoine (The National Institute of Cultural Heritage) trains curators specialized in archaeology.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Their mission is to enhance the objects discovered.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] The curator is the link between scientific knowledge, administrative regulations, heritage objects, and the public.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Among the goals of CRM are the identification, preservation, and maintenance of cultural sites on public and private lands, and the removal of culturally valuable materials from areas where they would otherwise be destroyed by human activity, such as proposed construction.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] This study examines whether significant archaeological sites are present in the area affected by the proposed construction.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] If these do exist, time and money must be allotted for their excavation.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] If initial survey and/or test excavations indicate the presence of an extraordinarily valuable site, the construction may be prohibited entirely.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Cultural resources management has been criticized.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] CRM is conducted by private companies that bid for projects by submitting proposals outlining the work to be done and the expected budget.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] The agency responsible for the construction often chooses the proposal that asks for the least funding.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] CRM archaeologists face time pressure, often forced to complete their work in much less time than might be allotted to a purely academic project.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Compounding the time pressure is the vetting process for site reports that CRM firms are required to submit to the appropriate State Historic Preservation Office (SHPO).
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] From the SHPO's perspective, there is no difference between a report submitted by a CRM firm operating under a tight deadline and a multi-year academic project.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] The ratio of open academic archaeology positions to the number of archaeology MA/MSc and PhD students is low.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] CRM, once an intellectual backwater for individuals with "strong backs and weak minds", has attracted these graduates, and CRM offices are increasingly staffed by advance degreed workers with a track record of producing scholarly articles, but who also have extensive CRM field experience.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] The protection of archaeological finds for the public from catastrophes, wars, and armed conflicts is increasingly being implemented internationally.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] This happens, on the one hand, through international agreements and, on the other hand, through organizations that monitor or enforce protection.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] United Nations, UNESCO, and Blue Shield International deal with the protection of cultural heritage, including archaeological sites.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] This also applies to the integration of United Nations peacekeeping.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Blue Shield International has undertaken various fact-finding missions in recent years to protect archaeological sites during the wars in Libya, Syria, Egypt, and Lebanon.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] The importance of archaeological finds for identity, tourism, and sustainable economic growth is repeatedly emphasized internationally.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] The president of Blue Shield International, Karl von Habsburg, said during a cultural property protection mission in Lebanon in April 2019 with the United Nations Interim Force in Lebanon: "Cultural assets are part of the identity of the people who live in a certain place.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] If you destroy their culture, you also destroy their identity.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Early archaeology was largely an attempt to uncover spectacular artifacts and features or to explore vast, mysterious abandoned cities, and was mostly carried out by upper-class, scholarly men.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] This general tendency laid the foundation for the modern popular view of archaeology and archaeologists.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Many of the public view archaeology as something only available to a narrow demographic.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] The job of archaeologist is depicted as a "romantic adventurist occupation", and as a hobby more than a job in the scientific community.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Cinema audiences form a notion of "who archaeologists are, why they do what they do, and how relationships to the past are constituted", and are often under the impression that all archaeology takes place in a distant and foreign land, only to collect monetarily or spiritually priceless artifacts.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] The modern depiction of archaeology has distorted the public's perception of what it is.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Much thorough and productive research has indeed been conducted in dramatic locales such as Copán and the Valley of the Kings, but the bulk of modern archaeological activity and finds is not so sensational.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Archaeological adventure stories tend to ignore the painstaking work involved in carrying out modern surveys, excavations, and data processing.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Some archaeologists refer to such off-the-mark portrayals as "pseudoarchaeology".
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p01] Archaeologists are also highly reliant on public support; the question of for whom they work is often discussed.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] Motivated by a desire to halt looting, curb pseudoarchaeology, and to help preserve archaeological sites through education and fostering public appreciation for the importance of archaeological heritage, archaeologists are mounting public-outreach campaigns.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] They seek to stop looting by combatting people who illegally take artifacts from protected sites, and by alerting people who live near archaeological sites of the threat of looting.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] Common methods of public outreach include press releases, encouraging school field trips to sites under excavation led by professional archaeologists, and making reports and publications accessible outside academia.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] Public appreciation of the significance of archaeology and archaeological sites often leads to improved protection from encroaching development or other threats.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] One audience for archaeologists' work is the public.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] Archaeologists increasingly realize that their work can benefit audiences outside the field and academia, and that they have a responsibility to educate and inform the public about archaeology.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] Local heritage awareness is aimed at increasing civic and individual pride through projects such as community excavation programs and better public presentations of archaeological sites and knowledge.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] Department of Agriculture, Forest Service (USFS) operates a volunteer archaeology and historic preservation program called the Passport in Time (PIT).
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] Volunteers work with professional USFS archaeologists and historians on national forests throughout the U.S.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] Volunteers are involved in all aspects of professional archaeology under expert supervision.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] Television programs, web videos, and social media can also bring an understanding of underwater archaeology to a broad audience.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] The *Mardi Gras* Shipwreck Project integrated a one-hour HD documentary, short videos for public viewing and video updates during the expedition as part of the educational outreach.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] Webcasting is also another tool for educational outreach.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] For one week in 2000 and 2001, live underwater video of the *Queen Anne's Revenge* Shipwreck Project was webcast to the Internet as a part of the *QAR DiveLive* educational program that reached thousands of children around the world.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] The American Academy of Underwater Sciences.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] Archived from the original on 19 February 2009.* Created and co-produced by Nautilus Productions and Marine Grafics, this project enabled students to talk to scientists and learn about methods and technologies used by the underwater archaeology team.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] In the UK, popular archaeology programs such as *Time Team* and *Meet the Ancestors* have resulted in a huge upsurge in public interest.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] Where possible, archaeologists now make more provisions for public involvement and outreach in larger projects than they once did, and many local archaeological organizations operate within the Community archaeology framework to expand public involvement in smaller-scale, more local projects.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] Archaeological excavation, however, is best undertaken by well-trained staff who can work quickly and accurately.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] Often, this requires observing the necessary health and safety and indemnity insurance requirements when working on a modern building site with tight deadlines.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] Certain charities and local government bodies sometimes offer places on research projects either as part of academic work or as a defined community project.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] There is also a flourishing industry selling places on commercial training excavations and archaeological holiday tours.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] Archaeologists prize local knowledge and often liaise with local historical and archaeological societies, which is one reason community archaeology projects are becoming more common.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] Often, archaeologists are assisted by the public in the locating of archaeological sites, which professional archaeologists have neither the funding nor the time to do.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] Archaeological Legacy Institute (ALI), is a registered 501[c] [3] non-profit, media and education corporation registered in Oregon in 1999.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] Pseudoarchaeology is an umbrella term for all activities that falsely claim to be archaeological but in fact violate commonly accepted and scientific archaeological practices.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] It includes much fictional archaeological work (discussed above), as well as some actual activity.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] Many non-fiction authors have ignored the scientific methods of processual archaeology, or the specific critiques of it contained in post-processualism.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] An example of this type is the writing of Erich von Däniken.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] His 1968 book, *Chariots of the Gods?*, together with many subsequent lesser-known works, expounds a theory of ancient contacts between human civilization on Earth and more technologically advanced extraterrestrial civilizations.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] This theory, known as palaeocontact theory, or Ancient astronaut theory, is not exclusively Däniken's, nor did the idea originate with him.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] Works of this nature are usually marked by the renunciation of well-established theories based on limited evidence and the interpretation of evidence with a preconceived theory in mind.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] Looting of archaeological sites is an ancient problem.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] For instance, many of the tombs of the Egyptian pharaohs were looted during antiquity.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] Archaeology stimulates interest in ancient objects, and people in search of artifacts or treasure cause damage to archaeological sites.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] The commercial and academic demand for artifacts contributes directly to the illicit antiquities trade.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] Smuggling antiquities abroad to private collectors has caused great cultural and economic damage in many countries whose governments lack the resources and/or the will to deter it.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] Looters damage and destroy archaeological sites, denying future generations information about their ethnic and cultural heritage.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] Indigenous peoples especially lose access to and control over their 'cultural resources', ultimately denying them the opportunity to know their past.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] Hodge the director of the Southwest Museum released a statement that the museum would no longer purchase or accept collections from looted contexts.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] The first conviction of the transport of artifacts illegally removed from private property under the Archaeological Resources Protection Act was in 1992 in the State of Indiana.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] Archaeologists trying to protect artifacts may be placed in danger by looters or locals trying to protect the artifacts from archaeologists, who are viewed as looters by the locals.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] Some historical archaeological sites are looted by metal detector hobbyists who search for artifacts using increasingly advanced technology.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] Efforts are underway among all major Archaeological organizations to increase education and legitimate cooperation between amateurs and professionals in the metal detecting community.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] While most looting is deliberate, accidental looting can occur when amateurs, unaware of the importance of archaeological rigor, collect artifacts from sites and place them in private collections.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] In the United States, examples such as the case of Kennewick Man have illustrated the tensions between Native Americans and archaeologists, which can be summarized as a conflict between a need to remain respectful toward sacred burial sites and the academic benefit from studying them.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] For years, American archaeologists dug on Indian burial grounds and other places considered sacred, removing artifacts and human remains to storage facilities for further study.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] In some cases, human remains were not even thoroughly studied but instead archived rather than reburied.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] Furthermore, Western archaeologists' views of the past often differ from those of tribal peoples.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] The West views time as linear; for many natives, it is cyclic.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] From a Western perspective, the past is long-gone; from a native perspective, disturbing the past can have dire consequences in the present.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] As a consequence, American Indians attempted to prevent the archaeological excavation of sites inhabited by their ancestors.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] At the same time, American archaeologists believed that the advancement of scientific knowledge justified continuing their studies.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] This contradictory situation was addressed by the Native American Graves Protection and Repatriation Act (NAGPRA, 1990), which sought to reach a compromise by limiting research institutions' right to possess human remains.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] In part due to the spirit of postprocessualism, some archaeologists have begun to actively enlist the assistance of indigenous peoples likely to be descended from those under study.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] Archaeologists have also been obliged to re-examine what constitutes an archaeological site in light of what native peoples consider sacred space.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] To many native peoples, natural features such as lakes, mountains, or even individual trees have cultural significance.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] Australian archaeologists have particularly explored this issue and attempted to survey these sites to help protect them from development.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] Such work requires close links and trust between archaeologists and the people they are trying to help and, at the same time, study.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] While this cooperation presents a new set of challenges and hurdles to fieldwork, it has benefits for all parties involved.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] Tribal elders cooperating with archaeologists can prevent the excavation of areas of sites that they consider sacred, while the archaeologists gain the elders' aid in interpreting their finds.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] There have also been active efforts to recruit Aboriginal peoples directly into the archaeological profession.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] A new trend in the heated controversy between First Nations groups and scientists is the repatriation of native artifacts to the original descendants.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] An example of this occurred on 21 June 2005, when community members and elders from a number of the 10 Algonquian nations in the Ottawa area convened on the Kitigan Zibi reservation near Maniwaki, Quebec, to inter ancestral human remains and burial goods—some dating back 6,000 years.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] It was not determined, however, if the remains were directly related to the Algonquin people who now inhabit the region.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] The remains may be of Iroquoian ancestry, since Iroquoian people inhabited the area before the Algonquin.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] Moreover, the oldest of these remains might have no relation at all to the Algonquin or Iroquois and belong to an earlier culture that previously inhabited the area.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] The remains and artifacts, including jewelry, tools and weapons, were originally excavated from various sites in the Ottawa Valley, including Morrison and the Allumette Islands.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] They had been part of the Canadian Museum of Civilization's research collection for decades, some since the late 19th century.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] Elders from various Algonquin communities conferred on an appropriate reburial, eventually deciding on traditional red cedar and birch bark boxes lined with red cedar chips, muskrat and beaver pelts.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] An inconspicuous rock mound marks the reburial site, where nearly 80 boxes of various sizes are buried.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] Because of this reburial, no further scientific study is possible.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] Although negotiations between the Kitigan Zibi community and the museum were at times tense, they reached an agreement.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] African Diaspora Archaeology is an area of study within the subfield of historical archaeology that studies those that have been forcibly transported through the Atlantic Slave Trade, the Trans-Saharan Slave Trade, and the Indian Ocean Slave Trade, as well as their descendants.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] Although of global relevance, most research has been conducted in the Americas and Africa.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] In the 1990s, anthropologist Michael Blakey was the director of research during the New York African Burial Ground Project where he initiated a protocol for collaborating with the African descendant community.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] In 2011, the Society of Black Archaeologists was created in the United States.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] Co-founders Ayana Omilade Flewellen, archaeologist at the University of California, Riverside and Justin Dunnavant, archaeologist and assistant professor of anthropology at the University of California, Los Angeles intend to build a restorative justice-based structure in archaeology.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] They suggest defining descendants not only in genealogical terms, but also to welcome input of African Americans whose ancestors had a shared historical experience in enslavement.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] The United States Senate unanimously passed a bill in December 2020 that centers African American cemeteries at risk in South Carolina.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] The bill is made to protect historic African burial grounds and can lead to the creation of an African American Burial Grounds Network.
[src:archaeology/archaeology-p02] Barbados, eight days after becoming a republic on November 30, 2021, announced plans for the construction of the *Newton Enslaved Burial Ground Memorial* as well as a museum dedicated to the history of the Atlantic slave trade.
